<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jarrett Still Seeks 1st Season Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FONTANA, Calif. (AP) -- Nine races, no wins.  
</P>
<P>
	That's the frustrating score for Dale Jarrett, who heads into  
Sunday's California 500 still looking for the 19th win of his 
Winston Cup career. 
</P>
<P>
	Jarrett had plenty of time to think about it Friday as rain  
washed away the opening day of practice and qualifying for Sunday's 
race at California Speedway. NASCAR planned to qualify the entire 
43-car field in one session of time trials sandwiched between two 
one-hour practice periods today. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess it has been frustrating because we're fortunate that  
in the last few years we have won some races,'' Jarrett said. ``I 
like to think that when we get down into the last few laps of a 
race that I know how to take care of business. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't done that this year and I've had a couple of  
opportunities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of those came last Sunday at Talladega Superspeedway, where  
Jarrett posted his third runner-up finish of the season. His Robert 
Yates Racing Ford trailing Dale Earnhardt's Chevrolet across the 
line by about two car-lengths. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I had myself in position, but I also realized that  
there wasn't a Ford out there that got in front and stayed there 
very long. And there were too many good cars behind me. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt like on that particular day my chance was going to come  
with help and trying to make a pass at the end,'' Jarrett added. 
``I just never got that opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One thing that Jarrett can take solace in is the fact that, even  
though he isn't among the seven drivers who have posted at least 
one win in the first nine races, he is second in the standings, 
trailing Jeff Burton by just 40 points. 
</P>
<P>
	A crash in the season opener in Daytona cost Jarrett a  
37th-place finish. Since then, his only finishes out of the top 
five have been 11th in Las Vegas and eighth in Martinsville. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel much better about our race team and our chances to win  
right now than I did say five or six races ago,'' Jarrett said. 
``Back then, we were finishing OK, but really weren't performing 
that well. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last few weeks, we've performed much better and I think  
we're ready to get into Victory Lane.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jarrett is certainly hoping that improvement in performance  
translates into a good finish Sunday on the 2-mile oval where he 
struggled last year. 
</P>
<P>
	After crashing in qualifying last year, Jarrett started 36th. He  
was moving steadily through the field before an engine failure 
relegated him to 41st place. 
</P>
<P>
	``Actually, I really like this racetrack,'' said Jarrett, who  
finished eighth in 1997 in the inaugural Winston Cup race at the 
California track. ``It's extremely fast, but there are a couple of 
grooves here. 
</P>
<P>
	``I found a groove here last year near the top of the track and  
found a very fast way around before we had our engine problem. It's 
a wide track that's going to let you have fun racing.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
