<HEADLINE> Moore Eyes Bosch Grand Prix Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAZARETH, Pa. (AP) -- It didn't matter that only two drivers got  
around tricky Nazareth Speedway faster than Greg Moore. 
</P>
<P>
	The CART points leader, foremost among critics of the  
aerodynamic package that has slowed the cars by more than 12 mph, 
thinks smaller wings will make for a caution-filled race that will 
be anything but a crowd pleaser. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the pace car may lead more laps than the winner,'' he  
said after practice Friday for Sunday's Bosch Grand Prix. ``Running 
here with so little downforce will be a dicey situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Moore, whose fast lap in a Mercedes-powered Reynard was  
169.080, has a plan for winning the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``Good pit stops,'' he said. ``There's not going to be much  
passing, so we'll do our passing in the pits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The way the cars were running, with the fast lap of Helio  
Castro-Neves at 172.357 in contrast to Patrick Carpentier's 1998 
record qualifying speed of 184.896, Moore might not have many to 
pass Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Between Castro-Neves and Moore on the speed chart is Mark  
Blundell. He also is unhappy with the wings. 
</P>
<P>
	``We used to run 5,000 pounds of downforce here,'' he said.  
``Now we're running 2,000 less. It took me 10 laps just get decent 
tire pressure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Castro-Neves so much faster than the rest with his Mercedes  
engine, is less concerned about the wings, downsized this year on 
the short ovals because CART thought the cars needed to be slowed 
in the interest of safety. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, it's bothering me a little less than the other  
guys,'' he said of his laps in one of only two Lola chassis in the 
field. 
</P>
<P>
	But he stopped short of saying he preferred the smaller wings.  
</P>
<P>
	Had he done so, Bryan Herta might have wondered about him.  
</P>
<P>
	``If they tell you they like them, they're lying,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Richie Hearn, like Herta far down on the speed chart, said he  
knew the wings would be a problem. But he didn't know just how bad 
they could get. 
</P>
<P>
	``The car is bad enough on its own,'' he said. ``But it's  
horrible in traffic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blundell's Reynard-Mercedes was much better, but he could see  
Hearn's point. 
</P>
<P>
	``Running by yourself is great, but running in the draft is very  
difficult,'' Blundell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore noticed that, but said drivers can't back down because a  
loss of momentum while following a car will make it virtually 
impossible to pass. He figures that will translate into countless 
mistakes and a dull race where no one will take any chances. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you want to watch carnage, sure, it will be entertaining,''  
Moore said. ``If you want to watch follow-the-leader, it'll be very 
entertaining.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fourth-fastest in practice was rookie sensation Juan Montoya,  
making his debut on an oval track. The 23-year-old Colombian, a 
winner two weekends ago in Long Beach, Calif., went 168.828. 
</P>
<P>
	Two-time Bosch Grand Prix winner Paul Tracy was next at 168.711.  
Adrian Fernandez, Christian Fittipaldi, Patrick Carpentier, 
Mauricio Gugelmin and two-time Nazareth winner Michael Andretti 
followed. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending champion Jimmy Vasser was 15th.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
