<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McDougal To Attend Steele Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Susan McDougal's lawyer says she plans to  
attend the opening of Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's latest 
case, the trial of a Virginia woman who provided helpful testimony 
for Mrs. McDougal a month ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Jury selection begins Monday in Alexandria, Va., for Julie Hiatt  
Steele, who is accused of obstructing Starr's investigation into 
the allegation by Kathleen Willey that President Clinton made an 
unwanted sexual advance toward her. 
</P>
<P>
	``Susan will be there front row center Monday morning in support  
of Julie,'' said McDougal lawyer Mark Geragos. He and his client 
were in Washington this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele's lawyer, Nancy Luque, has not sought to call Mrs.  
McDougal as a witness. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele's lawyers argued unsuccessfully in pretrial  
proceedings that Starr's office made a series of misrepresentations 
in order to trick Ms. Steele into making statements for which she 
subsequently was indicted. 
</P>
<P>
	In a risky move for a criminal defendant about to go on trial,  
Ms. Steele took the witness stand last month on behalf of Mrs. 
McDougal, who was being prosecuted in Little Rock, Ark., for 
refusing to testify to a grand jury in Starr's probe. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele maintained that she was prosecuted by Starr because  
she wouldn't support Mrs. Willey's account of the unwanted sexual 
advance by Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	A juror in McDougal's trial later said he found Ms. Steele's  
testimony compelling and that it gave added credibility to Mrs. 
McDougal's story that she was frightened of Starr's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal maintained she was prosecuted because she refused  
to falsely implicate the Clintons in wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal was acquitted on an obstruction count while the  
jury deadlocked on two criminal contempt charges. Starr is 
considering whether to seek a retrial on the two contempt charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
