<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Families of Captured Soldiers Happy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	For more than a month, they have kept the most American of  
vigils, with yellow ribbons, readied suitcases and tear-rimmed 
hopes for their captive soldier sons. 
</P>
<P>
	So while reports remained unofficial today that Steven Gonzales,  
Andrew Ramirez and Christopher Stone would soon be released by 
Serbian forces, those closest to them were hopeful the waiting was 
nearing an end. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just thank God so much for answering our prayers,'' Rosie  
Gonzales, Gonzales' mother, told reporters in Huntsville, Texas. 
``We can't wait to hold him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His father, Gilbert, said the family ``can't wait to watch (the  
soldiers) get on the bus and get out of there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzales, 22, Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles and Christopher Stone,  
25, of Smiths Creek, Mich., were taken captive March 31 while 
patrolling the Yugoslav-Macedonia border as part of a peacekeeping 
mission, seven days after NATO launched its bombing campaign in 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Late Saturday, families were yet to be told officially that the  
three would be freed, despite statements by the Rev. Jesse Jackson 
that the soldiers would travel Sunday to Croatia with his 
delegation. Jackson met with the soldiers on Friday in Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could say we're very happy,'' said Dorcas Reliford, the  
mother-in-law of Stone's sister, from her home near Smiths Creek. 
``We're waiting for confirmation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Los Angeles, Kathy Ross, a spokeswoman for Vivian Ramirez,  
Andrew's mother, expressed caution. 
</P>
<P>
	``The family is just kind of waiting until they know something  
concrete,'' Ms. Ross said. ``It has not gone at all through 
government channels.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Ross said the Ramirez family will not comment until they  
receive official word of his release. 
</P>
<P>
	But hope infused neighbors who came to teh Ramirez home, many  
bearing flowers. ``I feel wonderful now,'' said Lala Szalonek, 72, 
who brought a brimming vase. ``I'm excited. I'm shaking inside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tricia Stone, Stone's wife, was ``packed and ready to go'' in  
the event of her husband's release, said her stepmother, Lisa 
McKinney. 
</P>
<P>
	``She is praying and she is very hopeful that it is true,'' she  
said. Mrs. Stone and the couple's 4-year-old son, Ryan, have been 
staying with Ms. McKinney in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	In Capac, Mich., near Stone's hometown, Linda Eldred spent the  
day adorning her downtown floral-and-gift shop with new yellow bows 
-- and making many more to give away. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't known that kind of excitement since my brother and  
husband came home from Vietnam,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
