<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Florida OKs School Voucher Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- The nation's only statewide program to  
let students attend private schools at taxpayer expense is being 
praised as a historic reform -- and denigrated as the ruin of 
Florida's public schools. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Legislature on Friday sent a bill creating the voucher  
program to Gov. Jeb Bush, who had made the program a centerpiece of 
his campaign and one of his top priorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an effort to improve public schools, but it's also a  
recognition that when there's chronic failure it's just morally 
right to provide parents other options,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the plan, all students in the worst public schools,  
regardless of their income or their grades, will be eligible for 
vouchers ranging from $3,000 to $25,000 a year to help pay for 
private or parochial school tuition. 
</P>
<P>
	Schools will be graded A, B, C, D or F, based on student  
performance. Students in schools that get a failing grade will be 
entitled to go to private school. The tax money will be taken out 
of public education. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents have threatened to sue, claiming it will destroy  
public education and violate the constitutional separation of 
church and state. 
</P>
<P>
	``A bigger threat than any kid walking into a school with a gun  
is the Republican legislature putting all the schools under siege 
with vouchers,'' said Democratic Rep. Les Miller, minority leader 
of the Florida House. 
</P>
<P>
	Scores in only four of Florida's 3,000 public schools are now so  
bad they would qualify. But with tougher standards approved last 
year, the number of flunking schools could climb to 170. 
</P>
<P>
	Milwaukee and Cleveland have started voucher programs in recent  
years. Vermont has allowed tax dollars to be spent for private 
school tuition in rural areas for more than a century. Maine has a 
program similar to Vermont's. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida's Constitution specifically prohibits using taxpayer  
dollars to aid religion, said the Rev. Barry Lynn, executive 
director of Americans United for Separation of Church and State in 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't understand how voucher supporters could read the clear  
and unambiguous language of their state constitution and still 
think they can get away with this stunt,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington-based Institute for Justice, which has intervened  
in courts on behalf of school choice programs elsewhere, has 
promised to defend Florida's program. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the first money-back guarantee for public schools,''  
said Clint Bolick, the organization's litigation director. ``This 
program is a national model for school reform, and Gov. Jeb Bush 
deserves enormous credit for his vision and courage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leon Russell, president of the Florida State Conference of  
Branches of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored 
People, said his organization will try to block the program. Other 
opponents include the Florida PTA, the state's two teacher unions 
and the American Civil Liberties Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
