<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. POWs Close To Freedom  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Rev. Jesse Jackson traveled to Yugoslavia  
to win the freedom of three U.S. POWs, and that is exactly what he 
did. Jackson is to escort the three soldiers to Croatia -- and 
freedom -- on Sunday. Jackson will also carry a letter from Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic to President Clinton outlining steps 
to stop the conflict over Kosovo. Jackson said it includes a 
stunning offer by Milosevic to meet face-to-face with Clinton. 
Meanwhile, U.S. officials reacted cautiously to news that the three 
soldiers might be freed. 

</P>
<P>
	Dozens Said Killed in NATO Strike  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Dozens of people were killed today  
when a NATO missile struck a civilian bus crossing a bridge in 
Yugoslavia today, news reports and witnesses said. The private Beta 
news agency reported 60 people dead while the state-run Tanjug 
agency said 40 people had been killed. Pentagon officials said they 
could not confirm the reports, and NATO had no immediate comment on 
the attack. 

</P>
<P>
	Military Base Prepares for Refugees  
</P>
<P>
	FORT DIX, N.J. (AP) -- Workmen made repairs today as what once  
was the Army's largest basic training base prepared to become home 
to refugees from Kosovo. The first group of about 400 people is 
expected to arrive Tuesday at Fort Dix. A total of 2,000 to 3,000 
refugees are expected in coming weeks. The refugees will stay one 
to two weeks while arrangements are made for them to live with 
relatives or other sponsors. Of an estimated 500,000 ethnic 
Albanians in the United States, more than 200,000 are in the New 
York and New Jersey area. 

</P>
<P>
	Heston Takes Stand Against Gun Laws  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Charlton Heston took a defiant stand against  
gun-control laws today at the National Rifle Association's annual 
meeting in Denver. Heston also said the NRA isn't the villain in 
the Colorado school shooting. While the gun lobby held its annual 
meeting, thousands of opponents circled outside. Officials of the 
nation's largest group of gun owners -- at 2.8 million members -- 
refused to cancel the meeting despite requests from Mayor 
Wellington Webb and other local officials. ``We will not be silent 
or be told, `Do not come here, you are not welcome in your own 
land,''' Heston said. 

</P>
<P>
	3 Race Spectators Killed by Debris  
</P>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- Three spectators were killed when struck by  
debris that flew into the stands after a three-car crash in the 
VisionAire 500 Indy Racing League event tonight. Spectators sitting 
in the area where the crash occurred said a tire and suspension 
parts flew into the stands and struck the spectators. In addition 
to those killed, others were injured when hit in the grandstand at 
Lowe's Motor Speedway at Charlotte. 

</P>
<P>
	Ark. Boat Accident Claims 11 Lives  
</P>
<P>
	HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) -- Eleven people were killed today when an  
amphibious tourist boat sank. Passengers aboard the open-air boat 
panicked and scrambled for life preservers as it took on water and 
sank suddenly on Lake Hamilton near this popular tourist town, the 
city manager said. The dead included three children. The driver of 
the boat was among the survivors. Twenty people were on board and 
none were wearing life preservers, officials said. The boat sank in 
one or two minutes as it cruised less than a mile offshore, the 
city manager said. 

</P>
<P>
	WTO Deadlocked Over Leader Choice  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The World Trade Organization was deadlocked today  
as it made a desperate push to agree on a new director-general and 
avert a leadership vacuum at a crucial time for the global economy. 
At a bad-tempered meeting of the WTO's decision-making general 
council, supporters of former New Zealand Premier Mike Moore 
clashed with backers of Thai Deputy Prime Minister Supachai 
Panitchpakdi. The deadlock made it increasingly likely that the WTO 
would have to function without a leader. Yesterday, Italy's Renato 
Ruggiero left as head of the 134-member organization after a 
four-year term. 

</P>
<P>
	Philly Prison Alumni Hold Reunion  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Like high school chums with fond pasts to  
recall, former prisoners at one of Pennsylvania's oldest prisons 
returned today with the jailers who once guarded for their own 
``alumni reunion.'' The first-ever such social event at the 
170-year-old, stone-walled Eastern State Prison gave all who once 
dwelled behind its foreboding walls a chance to swap stories about 
their time at the prison. With more than 29 years having passed 
since the last prisoner left, those who gathered today said they 
were happy to return. 

</P>
<P>
	Charismatic Wins Kentucky Derby  
</P>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- The 125th Kentucky Derby was won today by  
a 30-1 shot, Charismatic. Trainer D. Wayne Lukas claimed his fourth 
Derby win and his third of the 1990s. Charismatic, ridden by Chris 
Antley, held off Menifee, with Lukas' other starter, Cat Thief, 
third. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
