<HEADLINE> Louisiana Election a Tight Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- It is an election made for conservatives.  
</P>
<P>
	Voters headed to the polls today to choose from among seven  
Republicans and two Democrats seeking the 1st Congressional 
District seat once held by Bob Livingston. A May 29 runoff was 
expected between the top two finishers. 
</P>
<P>
	The only independent poll conducted so far shows a close race  
between former Gov. Dave Treen, ophthalmologist Monica Monica and 
state Rep. David Vitter, all Republicans. They are the favorites, 
but it was the campaign of former Ku Klux Klan leader David Duke 
that attracted attention. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke placed a distant fourth in the poll of registered voters  
living in the middle class suburban New Orleans district with an 85 
percent white population. But he claims to have a huge pool of 
committed ``silent voters'' who rarely admit their support to 
pollsters. 
</P>
<P>
	After bombarding voters with phone messages against the Kwanzaa  
holiday and the creation of a stamp honoring Malcolm X, Duke 
appeared in television spots criticizing federal laws that ban 
segregation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all know that forced integration has been a disaster for  
our communities and schools,'' Duke says in the ad. ``We need at 
least one man in Congress to stand up for our heritage and 
rights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under Louisiana's open primary system, all nine candidates are  
on the same ballot. Voters don't have to cast ballots along party 
lines. 
</P>
<P>
	Debate has been dominated by talk of who is the most  
conservative, and there has been considerable sniping. 
</P>
<P>
	Treen supports public executions for drug dealers. One long shot  
hopeful brags that he is a 33-year-old virgin. All are for lower 
taxes and increased military spending. Most oppose abortion and 
more restrictions on gun ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	Monica says her father loved her so much he gave her the same  
name twice. 
</P>
<P>
	Livingston announced his resignation in December after admitting  
marital infidelities, although he was designated House 
Speaker-elect. He has endorsed Treen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
