<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teamsters Celebrate Hoffa Regime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Teamsters are gathering for a ceremonial  
inauguration for James P. Hoffa, sworn in last month as president 
of the union once led by his late father, Jimmy Hoffa. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 2,000 members of the International Brotherhood of Teamsters  
were expected at Saturday's event. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoffa was sworn in March 22 after a federal judge affirmed his  
December victory over Tom Leedham, who ran a candidate of the 
union's reform wing. Balloting was held after a campaign finance 
scandal overturned Ron Carey's 1996 re-election. Carey was barred 
from the rerun. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've indicated long ago that as long as President Hoffa keeps  
his pledge to work in the interests of Teamster members, I would 
support him,'' Leedham said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he doesn't keep that pledge, myself and thousands of  
Teamsters are going to hold his feet to the fire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The election was held under federal supervision as part of the  
union's deal with the Justice Department almost a decade ago to 
help loosen the grip of organized crime. 
</P>
<P>
	Election officer Michael Cherkasky certified the results of  
Hoffa's victory in January. However, he barred one of Hoffa's 
running mates from taking office. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoffa's father, Jimmy Hoffa, rose to the top of what was in 1957  
the nation's largest union. He remained in power for a decade until 
he was sent to prison for jury-tampering and fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Hoffa was an effective and highly popular labor leader  
who allegedly had close ties to organized crime. Jimmy Hoffa 
disappeared in 1975 and is presumed dead, a victim of Mafia 
infighting. 
</P>
<P>
	He rose through the ranks of the Teamsters from his job as a  
warehouseman while his son has worked for the 1.4 million-member 
union as a labor lawyer in Detroit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
