<HEADLINE> Derby Bettors Turn Out in Droves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- They turned out in waves Saturday at the  
125th Kentucky Derby, dipping deep into their wallets. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd of 151,051 at Churchill Downs was the second-largest  
in Derby history, behind only the 163,628 who attended the 
centennial running in 1974. A record crowd is unlikely now, because 
a huge section of the Downs infield was eaten up a decade ago with 
the addition of a turf track. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a day of seconds:  
</P>
<P>
	--Second-largest on-track wagering, $17,930,055 behind the  
$18,693,215 in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	--Second-largest off-track wagering, $66,117,097 behind the  
$70,248,647 in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	--Second-largest total wagering, $84,047,152 behind the  
$88,941,832, also in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
