<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Criticized on Gun Control Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Critics say Gov. George W. Bush did too  
little, too late when he voiced support for instant criminal 
background checks of gun buyers at gun shows in the wake of the 
Colorado school shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's either for instant checks or he's not. If the governor  
wants this to become law, he needs to make it happen,'' said Travis 
County Constable Bruce Elfant, one of those who worked for a bill 
killed in the Legislature that would have required such checks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really think if the governor would have shown some  
leadership early on ... he would have been widely applauded,'' 
Elfant of Austin said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's comments have put him in the middle of one of the  
touchiest issues in Republican politics -- gun control. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bush's waffling does not bode well for a presidential  
campaign. The gun show bill is a common-sense issue,'' the San 
Antonio Express-News said in an editorial published Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a pretty dicey issue in a Republican presidential  
primary,'' Elfant said. ``I am a Democrat, but I would be proud to 
stand with my governor if he would sign this into law. This is 
certainly not a partisan thing, believe me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal law requires instant criminal background checks for  
gun-show purchases from licensed dealers. But purchasing a firearm 
from an unlicensed seller at a gun show doesn't require the check. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill in the Legislature would have added those checks, too.  
But the House Public Safety Committee defeated the measure April 
20, only hours after the Colorado shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference the following day, Bush voiced his support  
for background checks. And last week, Bush said that while he still 
supports them, he believes it is too late to try to resurrect the 
gun show bill before the legislative session ends May 31. He called 
for federal action. 
</P>
<P>
	But Nina Butts, spokeswoman for the group Texans Against Gun  
Violence, said: ``If the governor is serious about tightening down 
on Texas gun shows, he can see that this law is passed. And it 
could go into effect Sept. 1. There is time left. It is not too 
late to pass it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	State Sen. Royce West, a Dallas Democrat who sponsored a similar  
bill, said Bush's personal popularity would be a plus in persuading 
lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gov. Bush is a very popular governor. I can't say for certain  
he could get it all the way through the legislative process, but it 
sure would give it a big boost,'' West said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush is pushing for legislation that would jail a juvenile  
caught illegally carrying a weapon until a judge had an opportunity 
to review the case. ``We're sending a signal that we don't want 
kids illegally carrying guns, and if they do they're going to jail. 
It's very serious,'' spokeswoman Karen Hughes said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
