<HEADLINE> 3 Spectators Hit by Debris in Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- At least three spectators were struck by  
debris that flew into the stands after a three-car crash in the 
VisionAire 500 Indy Racing League event Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The extent of the injuries and conditions of the spectators were  
not immediately known. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities cleared the section of the fourth-turn grandstands  
at Lowe's Motor Speedway, and the race was red-flagged while 
emergency workers attended to the injured. While medical personnel 
worked, track security employees stood around them holding up white 
sheets. 
</P>
<P>
	John Paul Jr. and Stan Wattles slammed hard into the fourth-turn  
retaining wall on lap 61 of the 208-lap event and went spinning 
down the front stretch, collecting the car of Scott Harrington. 
</P>
<P>
	Television replays could not show conclusively what kind of  
debris flew into the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the injured spectators was sitting in the 15th row, and  
the other two appeared to be about 10 rows higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Within minutes of the crash, all three of the drivers were  
examined at the infield care center and released. 
</P>
