<HEADLINE> Four Texas Cities Choose Mayors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Incumbent mayors headed for expected re-election  
victories Saturday in Dallas, San Antonio, El Paso and Brownsville. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Kirk, Dallas' first black mayor, was trying to become the  
city's first mayor to win consecutive four-year terms. 
</P>
<P>
	With 36 percent of the city's precincts counted, Kirk had 17,708  
votes, or nearly 74 percent, to 22 percent for his nearest rival, 
immigration lawyer Margaret Donnelly. Perennial candidate Jack 
Ludwig had less than 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In San Antonio, with 42 percent of the precincts counted, Peak  
had 26,253 votes, or 85 percent. Four challengers divided the rest 
about evenly. 
</P>
<P>
	El Paso Mayor Carlos Ramirez also led after early voting, with  
11,153, or 54 percent. City councilwoman Barbara Perez had 33 
percent, with two others splitting the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	As expected, turnout was light.  
</P>
<P>
	Results were unavailable from Brownsville, where Mayor Henry  
Gonzalez was being challenged by Blanca Sanchez Vela, wife of a 
federal judge. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirk, a lawyer and former Texas secretary of state, has promised  
to focus his second term on fixing streets, keeping the city safe 
and promoting economic development in south Dallas, the city's 
poorest district. 
</P>
<P>
	He spent much of his first four-year term pushing through  
referendums to build a sports arena and develop an area along the 
Trinity River near downtown. Each passed by fewer than 2,500 votes. 
</P>
<P>
	In San Antonio, Peak also sought a second term with a pledge to  
focus on basic city services. Peak's opponents were 
</P>
<P>
	El Paso Mayor Carlos Ramirez was expected to easily beat city  
councilwoman Barbara Perez, his closest competitor. 
</P>
<P>
	In Brownsville, Mayor Henry Gonzalez sought a third term against  
Blanca Sanchez Vela, wife of a federal judge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
