<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nuke Security Problems Nothing New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As concerns deepen that China may have stolen  
prized U.S. nuclear secrets, some Republicans are trying to link 
the espionage case to President Clinton and the controversy over 
his Asian-American fund raising. But so far Republicans keep 
turning up evidence of security flaws dating to the days when they 
controlled the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the bulk of the suspicious activity at the labs that is  
now the focus of intense FBI scrutiny started in the early to mid 
1980s, long before Clinton emerged on the national scene. 
</P>
<P>
	That's not to say some serious security breaches haven't  
occurred during the Clinton presidency. Just in the last week, 
evidence has emerged publicly that highly classified nuclear 
weapons computer files were transferred to an unsecured computer as 
late as 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	But if FBI suspicions prove correct, the nuclear scientist at  
the center of the controversy began to spy early during the Reagan 
administration. And the most serious breach detected so far, the 
loss of design information on the W-88 nuclear warhead, dates to 
the mid-1980s. Also, concerns about lax security at Energy 
Department labs, most notably at the one in Los Alamos, N.M., have 
been around for at least two decades. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't regard it as a political problem for Clinton, I regard  
it as a national security problem for the nation because the errors 
were made on the watches of both Republicans and Democrats,'' said 
Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., named by Senate Majority Leader Trent 
Lott, R-Miss., to follow the China espionage issue on behalf of the 
Senate GOP leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the criticism directed at Clinton focuses on the  
administration's response once internal concerns about possible 
espionage surfaced in 1995: 
</P>
<P>
	--An Energy Department counterintelligence official alleges  
higher-ups barred him from alerting Congress to the loss of W-88 
technology to China. 
</P>
<P>
	--FBI Director Louis Freeh told the Senate Intelligence Committee  
that the Justice Department in 1996 rejected an FBI bid to obtain a 
search warrant for the computer of Wen Ho Lee, the Los Alamos 
National Laboratory scientist suspected of funneling classified 
weapons information to China. Lee denies the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	--Some Republicans have called on White House National Security  
Adviser Sandy Berger to resign, claiming he was slow to grasp the 
seriousness of the espionage problem. Berger politely declined. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican senators are working on legislation that would  
transfer counterintelligence tasks at Los Alamos and two other labs 
from the Energy Department to the FBI, although the Energy 
Department's counterintelligence responsibilities already are run 
by an official from the FBI. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said he thought ``some are  
trying to politicize national security issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The China espionage issue is politically charged because  
Republicans, for much of Clinton's second term, have been trying to 
show that the White House has been more concerned about raising 
campaign money than protecting national security. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Republicans charged that China secretly funneled money  
to Democratic candidates and sought to leverage the contributions 
into political clout inside the White House. Last year, they 
alleged Clinton softened his policy on the export of satellite 
technology to China in exchange for Beijing's secret political 
largesse. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House steadfastly denies any connection.  
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, a member of the Senate Intelligence  
Committee, renewed his call last week for appointment of an 
independent counsel to investigate China's involvement in illegal 
political contributions. ``Here you have important, startling 
revelations about why we should have an independent counsel,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a floor speech last week, Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., who led a  
House investigation into the fund-raising controversy, focused on 
the espionage issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to get to the bottom of it,'' Burton said. ``And those  
who let this happen, for whatever reason, campaign contributions or 
because they like Chinese or whatever reason, they need to be held 
accountable and brought to justice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Robert Gates, who headed the CIA under President Bush, said  
any suggestion that Clinton tolerated Chinese espionage because of 
political donations is absurd. ``That's all just a measure of how 
poisonous the atmosphere has gotten in Washington,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gates said there are plenty of tough questions Clinton must  
answer, such as why security at the labs remained so lax well into 
his presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Intelligence Committee Chairman Richard Shelby, R-Ala.,  
said the most anyone can point to so far are ``inferences'' as to 
the administration's motives on China and security matters. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said it's clear that China began intensive spying in the  
United States as long ago as the late 1970s and into the 1980s when 
cultural and scientific exchanges with the United States showed the 
rulers in Beijing how far behind their country had fallen in 
weapons technology. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their nuclear weapons program was generation-one,'' Shelby  
said. The administration, he said, must rethink its China policy 
and realize that Beijing is not a ``strategic partner'' but a 
``strategic competitor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Regardless of whether the charges aimed at the Clinton  
administration pan out, it appears certain the GOP will pursue 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got dots all over the map and connecting them is the  
tough stuff,'' Specter said. ``But I believe that's what has to be 
done.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
