<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DNA Leads to Murder Charges in Fla. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- DNA collected from a crime scene almost 12  
years ago led to rape and murder charges against a man already 
sentenced to more than 200 years in prison, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alfred B. Harris was charged Friday with beating 71-year-old  
Raymond Brooks with an iron skillet and stabbing him to death on 
June 25, 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks' wife, Bertie, was taking out the trash and returned when  
she heard her husband of 52 years scream. She was hit in the face 
and raped, while her husband lay nearby in a pool of blood, police 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris, 33, had been a suspect in the case, but at the time  
police didn't have enough evidence to charge him, said Detective 
Kevin Durkin. 
</P>
<P>
	Durkin, who left the homicide squad in 1993 and returned last  
year, said he never forgot about the case. And since technology had 
improved greatly in the meantime, he decided to submit samples from 
the scene to the Florida Department of Law Enforcement crime lab in 
October. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks ago, semen taken from the crime scene was matched to  
hair belonging to Harris. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Brooks has agreed to testify against Harris, according to  
her daughter, Sharon Morgan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will have closure after the trial, and when this man goes  
to the electric chair,'' Ms. Morgan said. ``If he gets the death 
penalty, I'll be there to watch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harris was sentenced to more than 200 years on convictions for  
sexual battery, assault, grand theft, burglary and robbery in other 
crimes. Details of the crimes were not available Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
