<HEADLINE> Harry Caray Statue, Beer Linked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- To some, the beer cans placed in the outstretched  
hand of the statue of Harry Caray honor his memory. But others at 
Wrigley Field think their beloved announcer deserves a little more 
respect. 
</P>
<P>
	Since opening day, Cub fans have been placing bottles and cans  
in the hand of the 7-foot bronze statue that stands outside Wrigley 
in honor of Caray, who died last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was known for drinking beer, so what's the big deal?'' Amy  
Freeman said at Friday's game. ``Besides, this is a baseball park. 
People are supposed to be disrespectful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not so fast, said Kathleen Van Ella, the agent for the sculptors  
who created the statue. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the one hand, I smile with the fans,'' Van Ella said. ``On  
the other hand, I'm an art professional, and we cringe about this 
happening on a consistent basis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grant DePorter, managing partner of Harry Caray's Restaurant,  
thinks his friend would have been proud to be immortalized hoisting 
a beer -- so long as the brew is Bud. 
</P>
<P>
	``Harry started as a spokesman for Budweiser in 1954,'' DePorter  
said. ``One night, we sat around and figured he drank 70,000 beers 
in his lifetime -- not Bud Lite, not Miller, just Bud. We counted up 
a bunch of other drinks, too, but I don't want to comment on that 
number.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
