<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Imposes Serbia Trade Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton imposed a U.S. trade embargo  
on the Yugoslav republic of Serbia to begin ``tightening the 
noose'' around Slobodan Milosevic's military. U.S. officials 
reacted cautiously Saturday to news that three captive soldiers 
might be freed. 
</P>
<P>
	The sanctions forbid U.S. exports of oil, software and other  
items -- except for food and medicine -- to the Serbian province and 
coincide with a similar ban on oil products imposed by the European 
Union that also took effect Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The executive order, signed by Clinton on Friday night, also  
froze all official Yugoslav assets in the United States and banned 
imports from Serbia. Clinton exempted the Yugoslav province of 
Montenegro. 
</P>
<P>
	``With these strengthened sanctions, we will diminish the  
Belgrade regime's ability to continue its campaign of repression 
and defiance, while allowing needed supplies to reach victims of 
its reckless and brutal conduct,'' the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO, meanwhile, pressed ahead with the 39th day of airstrikes  
on Yugoslavia despite reports that Milosevic, the Yugoslav 
president, had agreed to release three U.S. soldiers to a 
delegation led by the Rev. Jesse Jackson. U.S. officials welcomed 
the news cautiously. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've seen the statements by Rev. Jackson and his delegation,  
and obviously we would welcome the release of the American 
servicemen,'' White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said the decision would be  
``good for the POWs and their families. We just have to wait and 
see what develops.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson briefed National Security Adviser Sandy Berger on the  
apparent success of his mission, and Berger relayed the news to 
Clinton, who was golfing with confidant Vernon Jordan in Virginia. 
Jackson also telephoned Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic appeared to be capitalizing on a diplomatic  
opportunity in his bid to soften his image. In an interview 
published Saturday by The Washington Times, the Yugoslav leader 
sought to distance himself from the ethnic cleansing by armed 
forces in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton formally notified Congress on Saturday about the  
embargo. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we continue to intensify the air campaign, this is another  
step in tightening the noose around President Milosevic's war 
machine,'' National Security Council spokesman David Leavy said. 
</P>
<P>
	European countries and the United States already had barred the  
sale of arms to Serbia and restricted financial transactions. The 
main thrust of the new order was to begin cutting off oil to 
Milosevic's forces. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been some concerns about the effects of a broad  
embargo on civilians. But NATO members issued a 17-point statement 
from their Washington summit last weekend vowing to ``tighten the 
constraints on the Belgrade regime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials were not immediately able to calculate  
what effect the broad embargo would have on the Serbian economy. 
NATO warplanes already have been targeting Yugoslav refineries. 
</P>
<P>
	Leavy said U.S. companies were expected to comply with the  
restrictions imposed through the Treasury and State departments, 
but there has been some disagreement about enforcing the oil 
embargo in the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	France has questioned the legality of a NATO proposal to ``visit  
and search'' cargo ships bound for Yugoslav ports. Russia hasn't 
decided whether to respect any embargo. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton exempted Montenegro from the sanctions because the NATO  
allies are concerned that any actions taken to weaken Milosevic 
could have a negative effect on the democratic leadership of the 
other Yugoslav republic. 
</P>
<P>
	In other developments Saturday:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Pentagon officials said they could not confirm Serb media  
reports that a NATO missile struck and killed civilians on a 
passenger bus in the capital of Kosovo. The bus was reportedly 
crossing a bridge north of Pristina that was not on the NATO target 
list for Friday or overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Air Force Maj. Gen. Charles Wald said NATO warplanes carried  
out the heaviest bombing to date on Friday, with about 600 flights 
over Yugoslavia and 71 targets hit. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Ten more B-52 bombers arrived in England.  
</P>
</TEXT>
