<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Reform Panel Growing in Size </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- At least 60 people -- 2 1/2 times the  
number originally planned -- are likely to serve on the 
International Olympic Committee's new reform panel, a senior 
official said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch had said previously that  
20-24 people would make up the IOC 2000 commission, which was set 
up in March to help the committee rebuild after the Olympics' 
biggest corruption scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	But so many IOC members have asked to be appointed that the  
panel has been expanded to a provisional list ``in excess of 60 
members,'' IOC executive board official Kevan Gosper said. 
</P>
<P>
	While acknowledging that the high number could appear unwieldy,  
Gosper said the commission will be broken into two or three working 
groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Originally, Samaranch said the panel would be divided equally  
between IOC members and outside experts. But Gosper said the 
expansion could skew the balance in favor of IOC members. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will try to avoid going away from the even split, but it  
could wind up being one-third from outside the IOC and two-thirds 
from inside,'' he said in an interview. ``It's not so easy to match 
outsiders with bigger numbers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The full list of members is expected to be finalized and  
announced Tuesday at a special meeting of the IOC executive board 
in Lausanne, Switzerland. A day earlier, the new eight-member IOC 
ethics committee will hold its first session. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC 2000 commission will hold its first meeting June 1-2 in  
Lausanne and make a preliminary report to the IOC general assembly 
two weeks later in Seoul, South Korea. The panel is scheduled to 
submit recommendations at a special IOC session at the end of the 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Until now, the IOC has confirmed the names of only six members  
of the reform commission: Samaranch, who will chair the panel; 
former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger; 1984 Los Angeles Games 
organizer Peter Ueberroth; U.S. Olympic Committee president Bill 
Hybl; IOC vice president Anita DeFrantz; and Italian industrialist 
Giovanni Agnelli. 
</P>
<P>
	Gosper said other outsiders likely to be appointed include Josep  
Miquel Abad, organizing president of the 1992 Barcelona Olympics, 
and Michel Barnier, co-organizer of the 1992 Albertville Winter 
Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The two other IOC vice presidents, Pal Schmitt and Dick Pound,  
will also serve on the panel, as will some other executive board 
members, Gosper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel's mandate is to study the restructuring of the IOC,  
including how members are appointed, age and term limits, and 
changes to the host city selection process. 
</P>
<P>
	The reforms are intended to reshape the IOC following the  
vote-buying scandal surrounding Salt Lake City's successful bid for 
the 2002 Winter Games. Ten IOC members have resigned or been 
expelled in the biggest purge in the committee's 105-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the U.S. Congress have harshly criticized the IOC and  
threatened to impose sanctions unless the committee adopts certain 
reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain, the Arizona Republican who chaired Commerce  
Committee hearings into the scandal last month, has accused the IOC 
of dragging its feet on reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch and other IOC officials have responded by accusing the  
United States of ``political interference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gosper said the IOC would not be pressured into changes.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's important you don't destabilize the existing strengths  
that have seen us through time,'' Gosper said. ``You don't throw 
out the baby with the bath water.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are the custodians of the Olympic movement,'' he said.  
``Our timetable should not be driven by people who really don't 
understand the movement. I don't think we should be thrown off 
course by outside advice, no matter how well intended.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
