<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T, CWA Negotiating Over Job Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- AT&AMP;T is in negotiations with its biggest union  
over eliminating thousands of technical jobs, a company spokesman 
said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Communications Workers of America, in a statement, said it  
has been discussing with AT&AMP;T ``the proposed downsizing of 2,400 to 
3,000 technicians who maintain the AT&AMP;T network nationwide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T spokesman Burke Stinson confirmed that, saying the company  
has proposed to the union a package -- including 80 to 104 weeks of 
severance pay based on seniority -- to persuade that number of U.S. 
employees to leave voluntarily. If employees don't agree to leave, 
AT&AMP;T would implement layoffs, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe that will happen, frankly,'' Stinson said.  
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T employs 140,000 people worldwide, with about 65,000 people  
in non-management positions. The CWA represents 42,000 U.S. workers 
at AT&AMP;T. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, network maintenance has become highly  
computerized and mechanized, thus lessening the need for in-house 
technicians to maintain and monitor the network, Stinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Eliminating the jobs would save AT&AMP;T $200 million a year, he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But CWA contends the cuts would hurt the quality of AT&AMP;T's  
service. 
</P>
<P>
	``AT&AMP;T is talking about eliminating half, or more, of the  
skilled technicians who maintain and monitor the AT&AMP;T network,'' 
said CWA Vice President Jim Irvine. ``Clearly losing this many 
skilled employees will have a detrimental impact on quality 
service,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T disagrees. ``We pride ourselves on our quality. That's why  
we've been investing billions of dollars in the technology that 
helps run our network,'' Stinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the workers eyed for cuts have been with AT&AMP;T for 25  
years or more, Stinson said, adding he expected most if not all 
would accept the package. 
</P>
<P>
	When AT&AMP;T offered a package last year to induce 11,000 managers  
to leave, 15,300 took it, Stinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	While not outlining the entire offer to CWA, Stinson said that  
in addition to the severance, all CWA workers will be eligible to 
take their pension in a lump sum this summer. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
