<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baltimore Prepares for Cuba Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Prosecutors have plans to handle up to 600  
arrests during protests surrounding Monday's game between a Cuban 
national team and the Orioles. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said they don't expect massive arrests. But Deputy  
State's Attorney Haven Kodeck said officials will be on hand to 
review any arrests and determine if a charge -- and a court date -- 
is warranted. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea is to keep from jamming the court system with cases  
that may not warrant arrest and could be handled in some other 
fashion. Kodeck said prosecutors will still charge protesters when 
it is deemed appropriate. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman with the Baltimore police said Saturday that  
officers patrolling outside Camden Yards will have the same leeway 
they always have in deciding whether it is appropriate to arrest 
someone, perhaps issuing a citation instead. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are just preparing for the inevitable, if there are arrests  
in large numbers,'' Kodeck said Saturday. ``We don't want to clog 
the system up on the back end instead of dealing with it on the 
front end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The spokeswoman, Angelique Cook-Hayes, said police anticipate  
the demonstrations will be peaceful. 
</P>
<P>
	Protests are planned both by those supporting an end to the U.S.  
embargo on Cuba and those opposing any move to improve relations 
with Cuban leader Fidel Castro. Police expect about 1,500 people. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, there is no anticipation of any kind of mass  
arrests,'' she said. ``If we have to make an arrest, we will.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kodeck said that during a meeting Friday officials were told  
there could be as many as 600 arrests, but that that would be a 
worse-case scenario. He said the meeting was called just to make 
sure law enforcement and the city's justice system were prepared. 
</P>
<P>
	With protesters expected to come to Baltimore from all over, at  
least one congressman, Rep. Bob Menendez, D-N.J., has said that 
lawsuits are possible if peaceful protesters are arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles already have their own plans for making sure  
protesters do not disturb the festivities surrounding Monday's game 
with the Cuban national team. 
</P>
<P>
	Protesters will be separated -- with one group at the north end  
of Eutaw Street, and the other at the south end -- in order to avoid 
any conflict between the two, said John Maroon, a spokesman for the 
Orioles. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, protest banners may not be displayed within the ballpark,  
in keeping with existing team policies, Maroon said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
