<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marine Pilot's Trial Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- The navigator of a jet that severed an  
Italian ski gondola cable, killing 20 people, admits he intended to 
deceive investigators by destroying a videotape shot during the 
flight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I made a hasty, stupid decision,'' Capt. Joseph Schweitzer,  
31, of Westbury, N.Y., testified Friday during the court-martial 
for his pilot, Capt. Richard Ashby, 32, of Mission Viejo, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby is being tried on charges of obstruction of justice and  
conspiracy to obstruct for allegedly helping Schweitzer get rid of 
the tape. Ashby, who was acquitted last month of manslaughter 
charges, faces up to 10 years in prison if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer testified that he destroyed the tape by throwing it  
in a bonfire, but that it was Ashby who took it out of the cockpit 
after an emergency landing. 
</P>
<P>
	Taking the tape ``was my idea,'' not Ashby's, Schweitzer said,  
testifying under a grant of immunity from prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer said he used the video camera during the EA-6B  
Prowler flight through the Alps on Feb. 3, 1998, and was concerned 
that he had filmed his face. Schweitzer said he was worried about 
how the public would regard the images of himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't deal with my face being superimposed on the blood  
in the snow,'' he said, explaining why he wanted to get rid of the 
tape that he originally shot as a souvenir of his six-month 
deployment to Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer pleaded guilty to the same obstruction charges facing  
Ashby and was sentenced to dismissal from the Marine Corps. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors contend Ashby knew a criminal investigation was  
likely when he landed his crippled jet and knowingly tried to throw 
off investigators. The defense contends the crew had no inkling of 
a criminal probe. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, an Italian magistrate testified he sent a  
notice of investigation to Ashby the day after the accident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
