<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillie Prison Alumni Hold Reunion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Like high school chums with fond pasts to  
recall, former prisoners at one of Pennsylvania's oldest prisons 
returned on Saturday with the jailers who once guarded for their 
own ``alumni reunion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first-ever such social event at the 170-year-old,  
stone-walled Eastern State Prison gave all who once dwelled behind 
its foreboding walls a chance to swap stories about their time at 
the prison. 
</P>
<P>
	With more than 29 years having passed since the last prisoner  
left, those who gathered Saturday said they were happy to return. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got good memories of that place,'' said Thomas Finn, a  
former guard. 
</P>
<P>
	One by one, the former inmates entered an outdoor corridor that  
separates one of the prison's dilapidated 14 cellblocks before 
shaking hands and walking through worn-down halls to find their old 
cells and posts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wow, I didn't realize it was this big!'' said retired guard  
Tony Guida, 67, as he surveyed a courtyard. It was his first time 
back inside the prison since it closed. 
</P>
<P>
	Eastern State opened in 1829, and went on to become the first  
prison to use the Pennsylvania System, which tried to reform 
inmates through isolation and spawned a century of controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	The original seven-cellblock prison was built to hold as many as  
250 inmates and used as a model for nearly 300 other prisons around 
the world, prison historians say. 
</P>
<P>
	Architect John Haviland's mission -- per a mandate from the state  
Legislature-- was to create an environment that forced inmates to 
become regretful and penitent. 
</P>
<P>
	It worked, according to Leo Benales, 75, who began serving a  
robbery conviction at Eastern State in 1942. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the impact and the enormity of what happened to me, (the  
prison) could have sucked the life out of me,'' Benales said. ``I 
was scared. That was an impact I'll never forget.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The reform system was eventually abandoned in the 20th century,  
and by 1925, nearly 1,700 inmates shared cells, meals and exercise 
time in group recreation areas. 
</P>
<P>
	The prison was closed in 1971, 26 years after a recommendation  
by the state Legislature. 
</P>
<P>
	Not everyone has fond memories of the place, said Richard  
Fulmer, a sociology professor at Millersville University. 
</P>
<P>
	``I started working there when I was 21,'' Fulmer said. ``One  
time, I was in my office alone with an inmate and he reached down 
for a knife. Instead of putting it on my throat, he stuck it in the 
blotter on my desk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eastern State developed a unique atmosphere as its inmates grew  
old while serving their typically long sentences. 
</P>
<P>
	``It tended to be a much more mellow place,'' said Sean Kelley,  
a prison historian. ``Most of the guards who spent a lot of time 
there were almost looked at as one of the guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tell that to Benales. In 1945, he said notorious bank robber  
``Slick'' Willie Sutton, who was housed in a cell across from his, 
asked him to help build a tunnel to escape. 
</P>
<P>
	Benales didn't go with him. Sutton and two others were caught  
soon afterward. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me he was an unsuccessful crook,'' Benales said. ``He spent  
more time in jail than he did robbing banks.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
