<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TV Stations Meeting Digital Deadline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Most TV stations required to begin digital  
broadcasts by Saturday are on schedule, broadcasters and federal 
regulators said. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of 40 ABC, CBS, NBC and Fox affiliates in the nation's  
top 10 TV markets are being required by the Federal Communications 
Commission to meet the May 1 deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many TV stations, as well as the 40 top-ten market stations  
subject to the May 1 deadline, have already moved ahead to launch 
their DTV operations,'' FCC Chairman Bill Kennard said in a 
statement Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Some stations in nine of the top 10 TV markets -- all but Chicago  
-- and in smaller markets voluntarily began offering digital 
broadcasts last November. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of 66 stations are either already providing digital  
broadcasts or plan to by May 1, the National Association of 
Broadcasters said Friday. Eventually, all TV stations will have to 
switch to higher-quality digital television before 2006. 
</P>
<P>
	Most stations offer digital versions of their regular TV shows.  
To receive them, people need to buy a pricey digital TV set. Some 
20,000 digital sets have been sold in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Digital technology lets broadcasters squeeze more video and data  
into existing channel space, giving them numerous options. They 
could use it to provide high definition TV, which offers sharper 
pictures than standard digital. They could also offer additional TV 
channels for sports or movies, or stock quotes and other data 
transmitted to home computers -- or a combination. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
