<HEADLINE> WTO Deadlocked on New Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The World Trade Organization was deadlocked  
Saturday as it made a desperate push to agree on a new 
director-general and avert a leadership vacuum at a crucial time 
for the global economy. 
</P>
<P>
	At a bad-tempered meeting of the WTO's decision-making general  
council, supporters of former New Zealand Premier Mike Moore 
clashed with backers of Thai Deputy Prime Minister Supachai 
Panitchpakdi. 
</P>
<P>
	``The atmosphere is testy, tense and not terribly pleasant,''  
said WTO spokesman Keith Rockwell. ``It is very clear that we don't 
have consensus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The crisis began Friday when Ali Mchumo, the WTO council  
chairman, proposed to delegates that Moore -- who is backed by the 
United States -- be approved by consensus because he had the support 
of 62 nations, three more than Supachai. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Japan, Malaysia, India and other Asian nations demanded  
a vote -- a move that would run against the WTO's time-honored 
practice of reaching decisions by consensus. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore supporters fiercely resisted the vote proposal, and the  
positions were even more entrenched Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The deadlock made it increasingly likely that the WTO would have  
to function without a leader. On Friday, Italy's Renato Ruggiero 
left as head of the 134-member organization after a four-year term. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear who would make executive decisions while the WTO  
is without a leader, and the organization has said it would not 
appoint an acting director. 
</P>
<P>
	The post of director-general is a key one, with a new round of  
trade talks looming and a ministerial conference coming up in 
Seattle in November. The organization is responsible for pushing 
through agreements to liberalize global commerce and set fair trade 
rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Supachai returned unexpectedly to Thailand early Saturday. It  
was not clear whether this was a sign that he conceded defeat or 
wanted further consultations with his government. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore stayed on, but his hopes of celebrating a speedy victory  
were evaporating. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the all-important backing of the United States,  
Moore had support from South America and the Caribbean. In the 
closing stages of the contest, he picked up backing in Africa to 
push him ahead of his rival. 
</P>
<P>
	Supachai, backed by Asia and Australia, the Middle East and  
several European countries, was long the front-runner and was 
widely perceived as the candidate of developing nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the WTO is now caught up in high-profile disputes between  
the United States and European Union over bananas and 
hormone-treated beef. On Friday, Washington said it would bring new 
cases before the WTO against Europe, India, South Korea, Canada and 
Argentina on Friday for alleged unfair trade practices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
