<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Pets Honored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Consider this -- more pets than presidents have  
been in the White House. Lots more. 
</P>
<P>
	In tribute to the more than 400 beloved felines and canines of  
administrations past, White House pet photos and memorabilia were 
to go on display today at the New York Public Library in an exhibit 
sponsored by The American Pet Products Manufacturers Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard not to love someone who's petting a dog,'' said Ron  
Elmore, a presidential pets expert and dean at the College of 
Veterinary Medicine at Kansas State University. ``Pets have been 
extremely important in our national history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At a preview of the exhibit Friday, Elmore recalled instances  
where the president's pet played a role in its master's political 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1952, Richard Nixon defended his candidacy for vice president  
when a story spread about a secret slush fund he kept. In a 
nationally televised address, Nixon did admit to taking one 
``gift'' -- his dog Checkers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The kids love the dog, and we're going to keep it!'' an  
emotional Nixon said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Checkers is given credit for saving Richard Nixon's political  
career,'' Elmore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Presidents and pets go all the way back. George Washington  
received his dog, Vulcan, from the Marquis de Lafayette, a 
Revolutionary War comrade, as a gift. James Garfield named his dog 
Veto as an indirect warning to Congress. Abraham Lincoln's beloved 
dog, Fido, was killed by a knife-wielding drunk. 
</P>
<P>
	More recently, Lyndon B. Johnson named one of his first dogs  
Little Beagle Johnson to ensure he would share in the family 
moniker. And President Bush's spaniel, Millie, had a best-seller, 
``Millie's Book, As Dictated to Barbara Bush,'' that outsold Bush's 
own memoirs. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, dogs are not the only animals to have lived at the  
White House. One photo at the exhibit features Ronald and Nancy 
Reagan riding horses, with Nancy holding a ``Just say no'' sign. 
There are also several photographs from the Kennedy administration, 
including one shot of Jacqueline Kennedy and John F. Kennedy, Jr. 
with two parakeets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
