<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Four Texas Cities Choose Mayors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Incumbent mayors of Dallas, El Paso and San  
Antonio rolled to huge wins Saturday, while Brownsville's mayor 
lost his bid for a third term. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Kirk, the first black mayor of Dallas, and Howard Peak of  
San Antonio both campaigned on themes of improving basic city 
services and played down promises of major civic projects. 
</P>
<P>
	With 85 percent of the vote counted, Kirk had 27,759 votes, or  
nearly 74 percent, to nearly 22 percent for immigration lawyer 
Margaret Donnelly. Perennial candidate Billy Jack Ludwig had 5 
percent. Turnout was well below 10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm ready, willing and relieved'' to declare victory, Kirk  
said. ``We've really turned this city around, and I'm looking 
forward to continuing that progress over the next four years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In San Antonio, with all votes counted, Peak had 40,388 votes,  
or 85 percent. Four challengers divided the rest about evenly. 
</P>
<P>
	El Paso Mayor Carlos Ramirez pulled in 30,253 votes, or 56  
percent, in the final count. City councilwoman Barbara Perez had 32 
percent, and two others split the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	In Brownsville, Henry Gonzalez was defeated by Blanca Sanchez  
Vela, wife of a federal judge. With all ballots counted, Ms. Vela 
received 4,700 votes, or 56 percent to Gonzalez's 44 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirk, a lawyer and former Texas secretary of state, promised to  
focus his second term on fixing Dallas streets, keeping the city 
safe and promoting economic development in south Dallas, the 
poorest part of town. 
</P>
<P>
	In San Antonio, Peak sought a second term with a pledge to focus  
on basic city services. Peak's opponents were Tony Garza, Joseph 
Rodriguez de Cisneros, Eloy Centeno and Louis Podesta. 
</P>
<P>
	In El Paso, Ramirez made waves by lobbying unsuccessfully with  
officials in Juarez, Mexico, to ban drinking by underage Americans. 
Mexico's legal drinking age is 18. He also got in a spat with the 
president of the city employees' association, which endorsed Ms. 
Perez. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
