<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 17:13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Derby Turning Into Wayne's World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- A horse whose future was so grim that he  
ran in a $62,000 claiming race in November won the Kentucky Derby. 
A horse who hadn't finished out of the money in his last 11 starts 
came in third. 
</P>
<P>
	The man who trained them both -- the horse that couldn't win and  
the horse that couldn't lose -- was the same. That should come as no 
surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	D. Wayne Lukas has four Derby wins now, a distinction shared by  
H.J. ``Derby Dick'' Thompson and surpassed only by Ben Jones, who 
won six. The difference between Lukas and the illustrious company 
he now keeps is that he can't imagine a Derby going on without him 
anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday marked the 125th running of this race. It also marked  
the 19th consecutive race that Lukas has managed to cull at least 
one entry from his coast-to-coast empire, for a staggering total of 
35. To put that into perspective, consider that he's had more Derby 
starters finish out of the money (26) than Thompson had starters 
(24), and more than twice as many as Jones (11). 
</P>
<P>
	The last time Lukas won this race was with Grindstone in 1996.  
That day, he also finished third, sixth, 10th and 18th in a 
19-horse field. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans of the racing game may want magic, but he gives them  
science. They may want folksy, but he gives them corporate. They 
may want quality, but he force-feeds them quantity. 
</P>
<P>
	And what anyone else in the thoroughbred game wants only matters  
so much any more. Because Lukas has turned this joint into Wayne's 
World, claiming as big a chunk of it as anyone. That includes rival 
trainers and two-time Derby winners Bob Baffert and Nick Zito, with 
whom he was competing for the unofficial title of trainer of the 
decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd be foolish to stand here and tell you I knew he was going  
to win this race,'' he said Saturday. ``But I'll say this: This 
horse had a great 60 days. And I'll say this: I misjudged this 
horse as much as any horse I've ever trained, and that's a lot.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
