<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fire 3, D.C. United 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Chris Armas scored a goal and had an assist on  
the game-winner five minutes later Saturday night as the Chicago 
Fire beat D.C. United 3-2 in a penalty-filled rematch of last 
season's MLS Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Stuard Dougal, a referee in Scotland's Premier League who was  
working the game as part of an MLS exchange program, handed out an 
MLS-record 11 cards. Of the 11, 10 were yellow and the other was 
red. The previous record was 10 cards. 
</P>
<P>
	Dougal, rated the No. 3 referee in Scotland, has given out 26  
cards in three games. 
</P>
<P>
	Armas scored the equalizer in the 77th minute, thanks to a  
little confusion between D.C. United defender Jeff Agoos and keeper 
Tom Presthus. Agoos was trying to screen Armas off the ball, 
waiting for Presthus to come out and grab it. But Presthus, who 
wasn't expected to play Saturday night because he's still 
recovering from a severe viral infection, apparently thought Agoos 
was going to clear the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	So Armas reached around Agoos and kicked it in, tying the game  
2-2. 
</P>
<P>
	Five minutes later, in the 82nd minute, Armas dribbled past  
Agoos and passed to Josh Wolff, who made it 3-2 on a sharp, 
diagonal kick. Jerzy Podbrozny also was credited with an assist on 
the goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago outshot D.C. 15-10, including 7-5 shots on goal. It was  
the Fire's first victory over D.C. United in the regular season. 
After two losses to D.C. in the regular season last year, the Fire 
beat the two-time defending champions 2-0 for the MLS Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	United started the night at a disadvantage, playing without four  
starters, and things quickly got worse. In the 16th minute, Brian 
Kamler was sent out of the game for elbowing, leaving D.C. a man 
down for the rest of the match. Ten minutes later, playmaker Marco 
Etcheverry left the game with a pulled right groin. 
</P>
<P>
	But United hung tough. Jaime Moreno tied the game 1-1 in the  
64th minute on a penalty kick after Lubos Kubik tripped him inside 
the 18-yard box. Moreno sent the kick toward the right side of the 
goal, and it sailed just past Zach Thornton's outstretched hands. 
</P>
<P>
	Three minutes later, D.C. United went ahead 2-1 on Roy  
Lassiter's goal on a nice cross from A.J. Wood. Fire defender 
Francis Okaroh tried to head off the ball but missed, and Lassiter 
put it in the net. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fire got its first goal on a questionable call with 30  
seconds left in the first half. Podbrozny had a free kick from 
about 25 yards out, and Presthus stopped it with a leaping block. 
But he never got control of the ball, and it dribbled out of his 
hands and landed just behind the goal line as he fell to the 
ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Though replays were unclear, referees said the entire ball was  
behind the line and gave Podbrozny the unassisted goal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
