<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Gov., Lt. Gov in Feud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- A feud between California's top two  
Democrats -- one that started over the serious issue of illegal 
immigrants -- has turned into a quarrel over parking spots. 
</P>
<P>
	The rift began two weeks ago, when Lt. Gov. Cruz Bustamante  
became upset over Gov. Gray Davis' decision not to fight 
Proposition 187, the voter-approved ban on most public services for 
illegal immigrants. The measure has been held up by legal 
challenges. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis opposes Proposition 187, but instead of fighting it  
head-on, he asked a federal court to submit the dispute to 
mediation. He said he felt bound to uphold the will of voters who 
approved the proposition in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Bustamante, who is Hispanic, lashed out with uncharacteristic  
emotion, describing how he stood proudly beside Davis on 
Inauguration Day as the governor proclaimed an end to ``wedge-issue 
politics'' in California. 
</P>
<P>
	Bustamante said he would file a friend-of-the-court motion  
against Proposition 187. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, this week, the governor's office told Bustamante's aides  
to surrender their nine parking spaces near the Capitol. The spaces 
had been on loan from the governor's office, the Davis camp said. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis spokesman Michael Bustamante, who is not related to the  
lieutenant governor, denied any connection between the Proposition 
187 feud and the parking shuffle, which he said was prompted by 
construction work. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could raise an eyebrow about the timing, but it just  
happened to happen this week,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The spat -- which doesn't affect the chauffeur-driven lieutenant  
governor -- prompted a round of news stories and editorials, some 
serious, some mocking, but all critical of Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	Bustamante and Davis agree on ``99 of 100 issues,'' Bustamante  
spokesman Phil Garcia said Friday. ``We really want to get back to 
policy, not parking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis and Bustamante, both moderates, won their offices as a  
team. Bustamante helped Davis among Hispanics, the fastest-growing 
segment of California voters, and Davis gave Bustamante more 
visibility. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, more than two dozen groups representing Hispanics and other  
minorities are applauding Bustamante in his dispute with Davis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
