<DOCNO> APW19990501.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 14:22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Derby Spectacle Extends Beyond Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Friends of Dave Wydalla put on the  
world's largest bachelor party Saturday in the infield at Churchill 
Downs on Derby Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Friends of the Atlanta man wore bright yellow T-shirts that  
read: ``D.e.b.b.i.e Does Derby'' -- or ``Dave's End of Being a 
Bachelor Incredible Extravaganza.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A couple of dozen young men and women danced and shouted, all  
while consuming large quantities of alcohol. 
</P>
<P>
	``Horse racing in Brazil is boring,'' said Marcos Rizzon, who  
flew in from Rio de Janeiro. ``This is just awesome. I'll 
definitely come back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the others among the 150,000 or so at Churchill Downs  
were at the track for one of the nation's largest and most festive 
sports events: the Kentucky Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	Amid the diamonds, pearls, feathers and ruffles of glitzy  
Millionaires' Row, celebrities such as Muhammad Ali, Wendy's 
founder Dave Thomas, country singer Travis Tritt, rapper Master P 
and actress Lynda Carter made the obligatory rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore and his wife, Tipper, attended their  
first Derby on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're coming back, now that we know what we're missing,'' Gore  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	White House officials said it was not a campaign event for Gore,  
who is running for the Democratic nomination for president. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, however, said Kentucky remains politically influential.  
</P>
<P>
	``Kentucky is always a player in the national election,'' Gore  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Derby, those who intend to stand out among the madness  
wear a hat. Something special. 
</P>
<P>
	``It took me about two weeks to put this together,'' said  
39-year-old Skip Koepnick of Grand Rapids, Mich., who said he has 
attended every Derby for the last 23 years. 
</P>
<P>
	He took a second to adjust his lid, describing in detail how the  
rotating horses on either side of a likeness of Churchill's famed 
twin spires were powered by a battery pack around his waist. 
</P>
<P>
	``I get a lot of positive response -- people wanting to take  
pictures and ask questions,'' he said. ``But that's what Derby Day 
is all about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The craziness begins early in the infield, where lines at the  
betting windows snaked 10 or 12 deep more than an hour before the 
11:30 a.m. first post. 
</P>
<P>
	Alcohol is readily available but is not supposed to be brought  
into the track. One group of enterprising men found the most 
creative smuggling method -- hiding bottles of bourbon in 
hollowed-out loaves of French bread. 
</P>
<P>
	Nothing is off limits in the infield -- from throwing a football  
or a Frisbee to lounging on inflatable sofas and easy chairs to 
fishing for red and blue plastic fish with toy poles in a baby pool 
surrounded by inflatable palm trees. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the third year for the pool and it gets bigger every  
year,'' said Liz Groves of Columbus, Ohio, who has been to each of 
the past 17 Derbys with her husband, Greg. ``The first year, we had 
diving competitions off coolers but they shut us down because we 
were too rowdy. We had lifeguards and everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For those put off by the anything-goes revelry of the infield,  
the paddock offered a more subdued experience. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this area, everyone is a fine southern gentleman or lady,''  
said Charles Matasich of Proctorville, Ohio, a spectator at each of 
the last 33 Derbys. ``This is the greatest sporting event in the 
world. The Breeders' Cup is for business. Derby Day is for nothing 
but pure fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At that moment, a well-dressed fan asked to have his picture  
taken with Matasich. Small wonder. Matasich is more commonly known 
around Churchill Downs as ``Derby Man,'' and his hat and jacket are 
cluttered with nearly 15 pounds of Derby pins, key chains and 
patches. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people here are the friendliest in the world,'' Matasich  
said. ``That's why most of them come back year after year.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
