<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 16:05:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Goldman Ups Stakes Minority Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After discussions with the Rev. Jesse Jackson, a  
minority-owned securities firm and one owned by a woman are getting 
larger and more lucrative roles in underwriting Goldman, Sachs &AMP; 
Co.'s initial public offering of stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Utendahl Capital Partners, considered the largest black-owned  
investment bank in the nation, and Muriel Siebert &AMP; Co. were moved 
up into the ``major bracket'' of underwriters, a grouping just 
below the top tiers of firms involved in the offering, a person 
close to the situation said Friday on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldman, Wall Street's largest privately held securities firm,  
expects to raise about $3 billion by selling a piece of itself to 
the public next week. Goldman will be its own lead underwriter. 
</P>
<P>
	The IPO is expected to be the second biggest in Wall Street  
history, behind the $4.4 billion sale of stock by Conoco Inc. last 
October. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson has waged a campaign to increase the number of  
minorities working on Wall Street and to give them greater ability 
to tap the Street's profitable businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent weeks, Jackson's Wall Street Project had fought for at  
least one firm, Utendahl, to be a co-manager of the Goldman deal. 
That's a first-tier ranking unprecedented on Wall Street that would 
have garnered Utendahl millions of dollars more in fees than it 
will make. 
</P>
<P>
	The source said that two other firms also moved to higher  
brackets, but not as high as Utendahl and Siebert. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty minority- or women-owned firms are included among the  
approximately 115 firms underwriting Goldman's stock. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the most inclusive (listing) in terms of the number of  
women and minority firms that I have seen,'' said Muriel Siebert, 
head of her self-named brokerage and the first woman, in 1967, to 
own a seat on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Goldman nor the Wall Street Project would comment  
Friday, except to say that they had been engaged in what a Goldman 
spokesman called ``a constructive dialogue regarding these 
issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Siebert acknowledged that no minority or woman-owned firm could  
handle the co-manager's position because of the millions of dollars 
in capital the underwriter would have to bring to the table. 
Essentially, an underwriter buys the stock then sells it to the 
public, garnering lucrative fees along the way. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the choosing is done based on ``how much capital is  
available to you,'' Siebert said. 
</P>
<P>
	Firms need an adequate capital reserve in case demand for the  
stock offering falls and the underwriting firm gets stuck with 
shares it is unable to sell. 
</P>
<P>
	``And none of these firms could take the responsibility if the  
market tanked,'' she said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
