<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Romney Outlines Olympic Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Fans at the 2002 Winter Olympics may have  
to stand at some venues or use outdoor toilets. 
</P>
<P>
	Pre-event concerts, usually free, could charge admission.  
</P>
<P>
	And anyone thinking of being a volunteer should be ready to pack  
their lunch. 
</P>
<P>
	Those are among the measures being considered by Salt Lake  
Organizing Committee head Mitt Romney as he tries to close a 
multimillion-dollar budget gap caused at least in part by the 
Olympic bribery scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	``One million here and one million there. It adds up,'' Romney  
said in a meeting with reporters and editors from The Washington 
Post, outlining his plans to pare $94 million from the games' 
budget. 
</P>
<P>
	Romney was traveling Saturday and could not be reached for  
further comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Olympic organizers are $300 million short of their goal of  
raising $859 million in contributions and in-kind services. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Olympic Committee officials blame the Salt Lake bribery  
scandal for the marketing woes, while some connected with the Salt 
Lake organizing effort have said marketing was slow even before the 
scandal hit late last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Salt Lake is heavily dependent on sponsors because the Winter  
Games don't bring in as much television and ticket revenue as the 
Summer Olympics. In addition, Utah is not underwriting the event 
the way recent hosts Japan and Norway did. 
</P>
<P>
	SLOC senior vice president Shelley Thomas said Saturday that the  
committee is looking to pare costs wherever it can in case funding 
doesn't meet expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with The Associated Press, Thomas said the cuts  
mentioned in the Post story were among those being considered but 
that no final decisions had been made. 
</P>
<P>
	Romney told the Post that, to trim $10 million, the games'  
18,000 volunteers will be asked to bring their own lunches rather 
than eating free meals at a cafeteria on site. Cutting back on 
signs and decorations for Salt Lake City will save $5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Another $1 million-$3 million could come from eliminating  
sections of bleachers at some outdoor events, cutting staff 
salaries, postponing staff hires and renting security radios 
instead of buying them. 
</P>
<P>
	``The kind of cuts we're talking about making will not diminish  
the excitement and the thrill of watching an Olympic sport,'' 
Thomas said. ``Whether or not you sit on one kind of bleacher or 
another makes very little difference to the experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But fans and volunteers aren't the only ones Romney said must  
make a ``visible commitment to frugality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	International Olympic Committee officials also will be asked to  
pick up the slack -- the IOC's hospitality budget will drop from $3 
million to $2 million and the traditional chauffeured limousines 
will be replaced with donated Chevy Blazers. 
</P>
<P>
	And SLOC board members will have to pay for their own meals and  
meet in the statehouse rather than hotels, a savings of $250,000. 
Thomas said the committee is practically under a hiring freeze, and 
any staff additions will be delayed till the last possible moment. 
</P>
<P>
	Romney also has suggested that the USOC or the IOC pay some of  
the $17 million required to operate certain venues before the games 
for competitors who want to train in Salt Lake City. 
</P>
<P>
	Romney and his staff insist the cuts will not affect the  
athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't mean they won't be fabulous games,'' Thomas said.  
``But they will not be opulent. They won't detract from the spirit 
of the fans or the competition.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
