<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 18:31:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Derby Turning Into Wayne's World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- A horse whose future was so grim that he  
ran in a $62,000 claiming race in February won the Kentucky Derby. 
A horse who hadn't finished out of the money in his last 11 starts 
came in third. 
</P>
<P>
	The man who trained them both -- the horse that couldn't win and  
the horse that couldn't lose -- was the same. That should come as no 
surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	D. Wayne Lukas has four Derby wins now, a distinction shared by  
H.J. ``Derby Dick'' Thompson and surpassed only by Ben Jones, who 
won six. The difference between Lukas and the illustrious company 
he now keeps is that he can't imagine a Derby going on without him 
anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday marked the 125th running of this race. It also marked  
the 19th consecutive race that Lukas has managed to cull at least 
one entry from his coast-to-coast empire, for a staggering total of 
35. To put that into perspective, consider that he's had more Derby 
starters finish out of the money (26) than Thompson had starters 
(24), and more than twice as many as Jones (11). 
</P>
<P>
	The last time Lukas won this race was with Grindstone in 1996.  
That day, he also finished third, sixth, 10th and 18th in a 
19-horse field. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans of the racing game may want magic, but he gives them  
science. They may want folksy, but he gives them corporate. They 
may want quality, but he force-feeds them quantity. 
</P>
<P>
	And what anyone else in the thoroughbred game wants only matters  
so much any more. Because Lukas has turned this joint into Wayne's 
World, claiming as big a chunk of it as anyone. That includes rival 
trainers and two-time Derby winners Bob Baffert and Nick Zito, with 
whom he was competing for the unofficial title of trainer of the 
decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd be foolish to stand here and tell you I knew he was going  
to win this race,'' he said Saturday. ``But I'll say this: This 
horse had a great 60 days. And I'll say this: I misjudged this 
horse as much as any horse I've ever trained, and that's a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was talking about Charismatic, not Cat Thief -- we think. Then  
again, with Lukas, you can never be sure. 
</P>
<P>
	Racing is not supposed to be about numbers, but they're  
unavoidable when his name comes up. So here are a few more, packed 
together: 
</P>
<P>
	Sometime in the next six weeks, he will top $200 million in  
purse earnings. The feat becomes even more staggering when you 
consider that the late Charlie Whittingham, whose career stretched 
more than 50 years, was the only other trainer to break the $100 
million barrier. 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas' mounts have won more than 500 graded stakes races, a  
staggering 7 percent of all the graded stakes in the last 20 years. 
He has won 13 Breeders' Cups -- more than any other and 11 Triple 
Crown races -- including six in a row from 1994 to 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	He doesn't cast spells over the game and its fans the way Jones  
and Whittingham did, but he doesn't have to. Overwhelming it 
apparently works just as well. 
</P>
<P>
	The reason he was ready to kiss Charismatic goodbye just six  
months ago is because he could. On any given day, a topflight 
trainer will have as many as 50 horses in his operation; Lukas' 
numbers tend to be between 100 and 200. 
</P>
<P>
	Most trainers can't keep track of that many horses, let alone  
find the cash to steer a few every year down the long and winding 
road that ends in the shadows of Churchill Downs' twin spires. 
Lukas believes he can't afford not to. 
</P>
<P>
	The real secret of his success is keeping them all separate.  
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Charismatic was eighth in the run down the  
backstretch and moved to fifth entering the final turn. By the time 
he was exiting the turn, he was third and driving, chasing Worldly 
Manner and Cat Thief. 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas, meanwhile, was watching from the grandstand, standing  
between Bill Young, who owned Cat Thief, and his wife, Laura, 
apparently a fan of 30-1 shot Charismatic, owned by Bob and Beverly 
Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	``You talk about being in a spot,'' Lukas recalled.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was standing with my dearest friend in the world, Bill  
Young, and Cat Thief surged to the front and I said, `He hit the 
front; here we go!' 
</P>
<P>
	``And then I started hollering at my wife because Charismatic is  
coming on the outside. At that point, I didn't know if I should 
jump up and down, holler, throw the program, or what. But then I 
just said, `I might as well go for it. It's going to happen.''' 
</P>
<P>
	It was a fitting conclusion to a week that saw Lukas elected to  
the Hall of Fame, because for all his accomplishments, he has 
inspired equal parts scorn and resentment. 
</P>
<P>
	His rivals are put off because he has grooms manicure the  
grounds around his stable and stack the bridles and buckets and 
blankets just so. They make fun of the creases in his jeans, and 
the starch in his manner. 
</P>
<P>
	And not surprising, they wondered aloud whether his string was  
running out the last two years, when Lukas sent Deeds Not Words 
(13th and last in 1997) and Cape Town (fifth in 1998) to the Derby 
starting line, and neither came back with much to show for it. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Lukas tried not to gloat, but he did tell a story  
that had been relayed to him by some friends. After Cape Town 
washed out, some people were having breakfast with Whittingham and 
started gloating about the bad week Lukas was having. 
</P>
<P>
	``And Charlie told them, `Shhhhh. Better to let the sleeping dog  
lie.''' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
