<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) -- Prosecutors are seeking arrest  
warrants for 10 Honduran landowners on charges of killing at least 
42 Indian leaders over the past 12 years in land disputes. 
</P>
<P>
	The special prosecutor for ethnic rights, Gilberto Sanchez  
Chandias, announced the action at a news conference Saturday. He 
did not release the names of those sought, saying that could 
interfere with police actions. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian groups have long accused landlords, woodcutters and some  
soldiers of killing their leaders in conflicts over land in central 
Honduras, where some 12,000 members of the Lenca tribe live. 
</P>
<P>
	About 10 percent of Honduras' 6.3 million people are Indians  
belonging to seven tribes. Most live in poverty and many have 
struggled against encroachments on their lands. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- With television cameras trained on  
the Congress floor, Brazilian politicians may have to watch what 
they mutter during debate. 
</P>
<P>
	Using footage from the parliamentary TV channel, a member of  
Congress is suing a colleague, alleging he swore at her and made 
impolite signals while she addressed the lower house last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Luiza Erundina did not hear the words of Marcio Reinaldo, who  
was sitting behind her, but she claims they can be lip-read from 
the footage, reported the O Globo newspaper Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Reinaldo, who made a signal calling for Erundina's microphone to  
be turned off, admitted being fed up with long and repetitive 
speeches but denied swearing, the daily said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Two men, one of them a Colombian, have been  
sentenced to more than 13 years in prison for drug and firearms 
offenses, the federal attorney general's office said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jorge Ivan Taborda Maya of Colombia was sentenced Wednesday to  
17 1/2 years in prison for transporting and possessing cocaine, the 
office said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The court in the central state of Jalisco also sentenced Oscar  
Enrique Diaz Gonzalez to 13 years and 5 months prison for 
possessing cocaine and other charges, including firearms offenses. 
</P>
<P>
	The two were captured in Guadalajara in May 1996 with 231 pounds  
of cocaine. Taborda transported cocaine in fruit trucks from 
Tapachula near the Guatemalan border, the attorney general's office 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Bank machines, cell phones, beepers and  
broadcasts were disrupted Saturday when Mexico's Solidaridad I 
communications satellite went out of service for the second time in 
four days. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers for Satelites Mexicanos, which runs the satellite,  
discovered a problem Saturday morning and had to take it out of 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	Fernando Moret, a spokesman for the company, told the Formato 21  
radio station that it was not clear how long the satellite would be 
out of service. He said the problem was not as serious as 
Wednesday's cutoff. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the satellite slipped slightly out of its orbit,  
causing scattered disruptions in television and radio broadcasts 
and beeper services. The problem was resolved within hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
