<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blues' OT Win Over Coyotes Typical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The St. Louis Blues earned another home playoff  
game, which may not necessarily be an advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blues' attempt to rally from a 3-1 series deficit against  
the Phoenix Coyotes continues on Sunday with Game 6. But both of 
their victories have come away from the Kiel Center, where they 
were only one game above .500 in the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, they concluded the regular season 14-4-1 on  
the road, and the home team has only one victory this series. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know that Phoenix did not want to make that trip,'' said  
wing Scott Young, whose overtime goal in Game 5 kept the Blues 
alive. ``Hopefully, that's a bit of an edge for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Losing 2-1 in Game 5 didn't seem to rob the Coyotes of any  
confidence, though. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've just got to keep our heads above water and be ready to  
go,'' captain Keith Tkachuk said. ``We won two games in their 
building before, and we can do it again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Game 6 will start only 36 hours after Young beat Nikolai  
Khabibulin to end Game 5, making this the series' second rapid 
turnaround. The Blues didn't return home until 5 a.m. Saturday, and 
canceled a scheduled workout. 
</P>
<P>
	That could be an advantage to the Coyotes, since 36-year-old  
Blues goalie Grant Fuhr had his worst game by far of the series the 
last time he played on little rest. Playing on 20 hours rest, Fuhr 
allowed four goals in 10 shots and was yanked early in the second 
period with the Blues trailing 4-0 in an eventual 5-4 loss in Game 
3. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to believe in yourself at this point in time,'' Fuhr  
said. ``We got one in overtime, and now we've got to go back home 
and dig deep and get another one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Coyotes also believe it's better to get right back on the  
ice after a loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to happen pretty quick, so we don't have much time  
to think about it,'' Tkachuk said. ``Which is good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The series has been extremely tight, with the last four games  
decided by one goal. The only exception is the Blues' 3-1 road 
victory in Game 1, and that combined with a lack of home-ice 
advantage makes for some uncertainty. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't really matter where you play nowadays, it seems,  
especially in our series,'' Coyotes right wing Rick Tocchet said. 
``We're a good road club, St. Louis is a good road club, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rallying from a 3-1 deficit isn't as rare of a feat as it used  
to be. Six teams have done it in the 1990s and that includes the 
Blues, who beat Detroit in the first round in 1991. Twice this 
decade, the Coyotes, in their former guise as the Winnipeg Jets, 
have been the victims. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully with a good effort, maybe a few breaks, we can win  
Game 6,'' right wing Terry Yake said. ``When you've got a Game 7, 
it's a crapshoot, it's anybody's series, and right now that's what 
we're hoping for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tocchet said the Coyotes could have buried the Blues in Game 3  
with the early 4-0 lead, but relaxed and let St. Louis rally to 
lose a tight 5-4 game. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still won the game, but that's a lesson,'' Tocchet said.  
``You've got to put your foot on the snake and kill it. It can come 
back and bite you.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990501.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 14:12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands Rally Against Army School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Singing and carrying a colorful array of  
banners, thousands of protesters rallied near the White House 
Saturday against an Army school in Georgia that has trained Latin 
American soldiers who were later accused of human rights abuses. 
</P>
<P>
	With a large black-and-white skull topped with a graduate's  
mortarboard as a backdrop, speakers from Haiti, Mexico, Honduras, 
Colombia, Chile and Guatemala detailed what they said were acts of 
torture and repression carried out by the school's graduates. 
</P>
<P>
	The School of the Americas, in Georgia, has trained more than  
50,000 Latin American soldiers over the past 50 years and has been 
targeted by church activists since the disclosure that 19 of the 25 
Salvadoran officers linked to the 1989 slaying of six Jesuit 
priests were graduates. The protesters want it closed. 
</P>
<P>
	Defenders of the school maintain it should not be held  
responsible for the acts of a few of its graduates. They argue the 
school, which has added human rights courses in recent years, plays 
an important part in the U.S. effort to foster democracy in Latin 
America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990501.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 16:12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Good Times Roll for Many Americans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Sumaya Hoggard steps out of her home and sees her family's  
future in the empty lot next door in Chicago's trendy Bucktown 
neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Hoggard and her husband, Troy, both architects, plan to  
build a three-bedroom, 2 1/2-bath house on the 3,500-square-foot lot, 
with an open floor plan, fireplaces, courtyard lawn and modern 
interiors. 
</P>
<P>
	The cost will be astronomical, but the first-time mother-to-be  
smiles confidently: the future is bright and, like many Americans, 
they're letting the good times roll. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a spur-of-the-moment decision,'' she says, one that  
required dipping into savings. ``It's obviously going to be more 
expensive to build a home than to buy one, but we wanted to design 
it ourselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the economy continuing to grow at a remarkable rate, many  
Americans are confidently buying more cars and homes and expanding 
their businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department reported Friday that the economy grew at  
a strong 4.5 percent rate in the first three months of the year as 
consumers spent at the fastest pace in more than a decade. Housing 
construction, which has been propelled by low mortgage rates and 
low unemployment, jumped 15.6 percent, the fastest advance in a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The good economy is also hindering us,'' Mrs. Hoggard notes.  
``The market is so tight that any builder you talk to has so much 
work to do, so many projects, that they don't have the time to do 
what we want done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The strong spending has been bolstered by the lowest  
unemployment in nearly three decades, record highs for consumer 
confidence, and a soaring stock market that now is reaching for the 
11,000 mark. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers are so confident that they are dipping heavily into  
savings to finance their buying binge. The personal savings rate, 
savings as a percentage of disposable income, dropped to a record 
minus-0.5 percent in the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	But even with the strong consumer demand and tight labor  
markets, inflation remained a no-show in the first three months of 
the year. A price measure tied to the gross domestic product rose 
at an annual rate of just 1 percent, little changed from a 0.9 
percent increase in the fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have the best-of-both-worlds situation when it comes to the  
ordinary citizen: jobs are available and inflation is in check,'' 
said Robert Dederick, an economist with Northern Trust Co. in 
Chicago. ``People are feeling good and they're spending, and even 
though this economic expansion has run a long time, it doesn't show 
any signs that its demise is anywhere imminent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Klein Jewelers in downtown Portland, Ore., Kathie Hellwege  
greets a business-suited customer who says he's ``shopping for a 
special lady.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One thing Hellwege has noticed about the economy is that gold  
jewelry is not just for weddings and anniversaries anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're buying it for more occasions, just little things,''  
she says. ``A lot of ladies are buying little things for 
themselves. Guys will buy things for themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Down the street, John Doyle stands at a cart, busy serving up  
fish-shaped cornbreads with various fillings for $1 each to a 
hungry lunch crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	He and his partner, Sean Brown, made their startup money  
teaching English in Asia -- before an economic crisis swept across 
the world while leaving America largely unaffected. The cash helped 
them buy a house, and the good economic times here are giving them 
ideas of expanding their business -- named No Fish! Go Fish! -- into 
a sit-down restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	``This business has been better than our house,'' he says.  
``Right now we're just putting all of it into building up our 
business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others haven't seen the benefits of the strong economy, but  
share the confidence. 
</P>
<P>
	William Walker, 33, of Philadelphia, has been out of work for  
nearly three years and is living in a homeless shelter. 
</P>
<P>
	But he still keeps track of the stock market and the Dow as he  
plans to return to school in the fall to study civil engineering. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unbelievable. I wish I was able to take part in it,'' he  
says as he walks to pick up a check at the social services office. 
``By the end of the year, I think it could hit 13 (thousand).'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Associated Press writers Genaro Armas in  
Philadelphia and Cindy Simmons in Portland, Ore., contributed to 
this story. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
