<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Notes From the 125th Kentucky Derby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- For bettors enthused about Worldly  
Manner, there was good news from England early Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	At Newmarket, Dubai-trained Island Sands won the 2,000 Guineas  
race, the first Classic of the British racing season, by a 
half-length over Enrique. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Island Sands and Worldly Manner are owned by Godolphin  
Racing, the Dubai branch of Sheikh Maktoum al Maktoum's racing 
operation. Both are trained by Saeed bin Suroor. And both were 
unraced in about eight months going into Saturday's races. 
</P>
<P>
	Island Sands was coming off a layoff of 260 days since his last  
formal race. And Worldly Manner last ran at Del Mar on Sept. 8, 
when he won the Del Mar Futurity by five lengths. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheikh Maktoum purchased Worldly Manner from his breeders, John  
and Betty Mabee, last summer for $5 million and kept the horse in 
Dubai over the winter. His only race this year prior to the Derby 
was in an informal trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Many have questioned whether Worldly Manner can win the Derby  
without undergoing the usual run of American prep races. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *WIRE TO WIRE:*With 19 horses in the field, Saturday's Kentucky  
Derby figured to be a wide-open affair. One thing it did not figure 
to involve was a wire-to-wire winner. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 124-year history of the race prior to Saturday, just 21  
horses had won while leading at each point of call during the race. 
And only four horses had won wire-to-wire in the last 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Riva Ridge led all the way in 1972, Bold Forbes in 1976, Spend a  
Buck in 1985 and, most recently, the filly Winning Colors in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *IN THE BLINK:* Five horses went into the Derby having benefited  
from the addition of blinkers. 
</P>
<P>
	Adonis, First American, General Challenge, Prime Timber and  
Three Ring all added blinkers this spring, then won their first 
race with the devices, which limit a horse's peripheral vision, 
forcing them to focus on the road ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	Adonis added blinkers, then won the Wood Memorial, while First  
American put them on for his Flamingo Stakes win. Prime Timber won 
the San Felipe in his first start with blinkers, then finished 
second in the Santa Anita Derby to General Challenge, a first-time 
blinkers wearer. And Three Ring had two straight easy wins after 
she added blinkers, including a 14 3/4-length win in the Davona Dale. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FRESH VOICE:* Even before the horses crossed the finish line in  
the 125th Kentucky Derby, Luke Kruytbosch fulfilled the dream of a 
lifetime. 
</P>
<P>
	Just one week into his new job as Churchill Downs' on-track  
announcer, the 36-year-old Kruytbosch called his first Kentucky 
Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I first started calling races, the general manager who  
hired me asked about my goals and I told him that one day I wanted 
to call the Kentucky Derby,'' he said. ``I just get chills thinking 
about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kruytbosch was just the fifth on-track announcer at Churchill  
since the track installed a public address system in 1940. He took 
over from Kurt Becker, who resigned after a brief two-year tenure. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to coming to Churchill, Kruytbosch was the track announcer  
at Hollywood Park in Los Angeles, where he had been since 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
