<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Moehler Ejected for Scuffing Ball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Brian Moehler walked to the dugout,  
nothing in his stride or demeanor indicating he had just been 
thrown out of a game for something he insists he didn't do. 
</P>
<P>
	The Detroit Tigers right-hander denied having a small piece of  
sandpaper attached to his left thumb when he was ejected during 
Saturday night's 4-3 loss to the Tampa Bay Devil Rays. 
</P>
<P>
	He said it was just not his nature to protest the finding of  
umpire Larry Barnett in the seventh inning. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not the type of person that's ill-natured or going to go  
up there and scream and yell and make a big stink out of it,'' said 
Moehler, who probably faces a suspension. ``He was doing his job. 
... I was so shocked.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Devil Rays became suspicious of the Tigers pitcher because  
the movement on some of his pitches seemed uncharacteristic of the 
right-hander, who allowed four runs, seven hits, walked one and 
struck out five in 6 1-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Tampa Bay manager Larry Rothschild asked Barnett, the plate  
umpire, the procedure for checking Moehler at the beginning of the 
seventh inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Three batters latter -- after Paul Sorrento and Mike DiFelice had  
singled with one out -- Rothschild went to Barnett again and 
requested he take a close look at the pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	``I ran out there and I said, `Let me see your glove.' He took  
his glove off and he held his thumb like that (facing his palm four 
fingers up). I looked at his glove and then I said, `Give me your 
thumb.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Barnett said the sandpaper, which he described as smaller than a  
dime, appeared to be glued to Moehler's thumb. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did not confiscate it. Had it been on his glove, I would  
have taken his glove. I did not take the sandpaper off. As God is 
my witness, it was there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was not clear that Moehler was ejected. There was no visible  
reaction from the Tigers or Devil Rays and -- as far as Detroit 
manager Larry Parrish was concerned -- time for a pitching change 
anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	Reliever Sean Runyan walked the next batter, Kevin Stocker, to  
load the bases, then gave up Randy Winn's sacrifice fly that broke 
a 3-3 tie. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know exactly what went on out there. I know what Larry  
said, the reason for it,'' Parrish said. ``As far as I was 
concerned, I'm just worried about bringing a pitcher in to get the 
next guy out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parrish called the Devil Rays decision to ask Barnett to check  
Moehler ``a bootleg thing to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not saying that Mo does or does not. I'm just saying that  
in the major leagues, as long as I can remember, that's sort of 
been part of baseball,'' Parrish said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not a pitching staff in baseball that don't have guys  
that deface a ball occasionally, including Roger Clemens and Nolan 
Ryan. Even guys that throw like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tampa Bay slugger Jose Canseco, who leads the majors with 10  
homers, was 0-for-3 with one strikeout against Moehler. He seemed 
amused by the ejection. 
</P>
<P>
	``So, he's a carpenter,'' he joked about the sandpaper. ``Maybe  
I should cork my bat now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rothschild, a former pitching coach, said he wouldn't have  
protested unless he was certain Moehler was cheating. He didn't 
have harsh words for the Detroit pitcher, though. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not the first time it's ever been done, believe me. And  
it's not going to be the last time,'' the Tampa Bay manager said. 
``Frankly, I don't blame the guy. I know the rules of the game, and 
everything else. But ...'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rothschild didn't finish the sentence.  
</P>
<P>
	Moehler said he will consider appealing the finding. Asked if he  
could win, he shrugged. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know. I would like to, but who's word are you going to  
believe? And Barnett's a good umpire. He was doing his job. I'm not 
mad at anybody in any sense.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
