<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Earnhardt Needs Good Day in Calif. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FONTANA, Calif. (AP) -- Dale Earnhardt doesn't call it the moment  
of truth, although he admits the California 500 could be a telling 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven-time Winston Cup champion is coming off a victory last  
Sunday in Talladega, Ala., that ended a 40-race winless string and 
boosted Earnhardt into a tie with teammate Mike Skinner for ninth 
place in the season standings. 
</P>
<P>
	If Earnhardt, who turned 48 on Thursday, is to really compete  
for his first series title since 1994, he has to build on that win, 
piling up some top fives and top 10s over the next few weeks and 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to keep it going,'' said Earnhardt, who had only three  
top 10s in the eight races prior to Talladega. ``We proved 
something to ourselves and some other people in that race. I think 
it gave everybody on the (Richard) Childress team some new 
confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His jump into the top 10 was a timely one since qualifying for  
Sunday's race was rained out and the front of the 43-car field was 
determined by car-owner points, meaning Earnhardt's Chevrolet will 
start 10th on the 2-mile California Speedway oval. 
</P>
<P>
	That's a big improvement over last year, when he struggled to  
qualify and had to use the provisional berth for former series 
champions to get the 43rd starting spot. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his poor qualifying effort, Earnhardt ran well in the  
race and finished ninth for the second straight year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like this track,'' Earnhardt said. ``You can really race  
here. It's wide, like Michigan, but it doesn't have the high 
banking like Michigan. You've got a couple of (racing) grooves and 
you can really race each other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Until last Sunday, Earnhardt had not led a lap this season. Now,  
he said, it's ``very important ... to keep some consistency going'' 
at California. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've made some mistakes and we've had some bad luck this  
year, but we know this team is capable of running up front,'' he 
said. ``We've got great cars, good engines and the pit stops are as 
good as anybody's. Now, we just have to go out and put it all 
together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Series points leader Jeff Burton will start at the front,  
alongside fellow Ford driver Dale Jarrett. 
</P>
<P>
	Right behind will be the Ford of defending race champion Mark  
Martin, the Pontiac of Bobby Labonte and the Chevrolet of Jeff 
Gordon, the winner of the inaugural Winston Cup race here in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon, the two-time defending Winston Cup champion, crashed at  
Talladega and finished 36th, dropping him to fifth for the season, 
210 points behind Burton. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's time to be consistent,'' Gordon said. ``There's still 25  
races this season, so all we have to do to get back into it is go 
out there and finish races and start piling up those top fives and 
top 10s. I know we're still in this thing very solid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like Earnhardt, Gordon says California Speedway, where he has  
finished first and fourth, is a good place to begin moving up. 
</P>
<P>
	``After you crash like we did last week, sometimes you can get a  
little tentative the next week, especially if you're at a track 
that's real tough,'' Gordon said. ``But this place is nice and wide 
and racey. You can go out and run hard and get yourself into a good 
rhythm. I'm looking forward to getting going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon said that ``nobody who really knows Winston Cup racing  
ever doubted that Dale Earnhardt can still win. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now that he's up front again, it just makes it harder for us,  
another tough guy to beat.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
