<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sees Few Images of War Damages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The black and white video is grainy, recorded  
by a shuddering camera from thousands of feet up. A crosshatch 
cursor targets a radar dish. An F-15 drops its bomb. Suddenly, a 
church pops into view. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. jet fighter crew quickly steers the optically guided  
bomb into a field, missing the Serbian air defense radar and the 
church. 
</P>
<P>
	That dramatic video of NATO airstrikes in Yugoslavia, released  
by the Pentagon, reached the TV news and Americans' homes. But 
scores of other shots and satellite photos of precision-guided 
bombs hitting bridges, fuel and arms depots, Serb army barracks and 
command centers haven't received much public play. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the driving images of war have been of ethnic Albanians  
violently chased from Kosovo by Serb forces, and Serb TV shots of 
civilians accidentally killed by NATO bombs, a downed U.S. F-117 
stealth fighter and three captured U.S. soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic agreed Saturday to release  
the soliders, who have been held for more than a month, to the Rev. 
Jesse Jackson, who led a peace mission to Belgrade. They are to 
leave the country on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Five weeks into the airstrikes, media and military experts say  
Milosevic has shaped the story so far. Meanwhile, the Pentagon and 
NATO are forced to combat public perception that the air campaign 
isn't damaging Serb forces enough and that a ground invasion might 
be necessary for victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're winning the war, but we're losing the propaganda war,''  
said Chuck Vollmer, a former Vietnam fighter pilot. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Lichter, president of the Center for Media and Public  
Affairs, said that during the 1991 Gulf War, Pentagon footage of 
precision-guided bombs destroying Iraqi targets flooded TV news 
worldwide, giving coalition forces a PR boost. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Lichter said, the novelty of high-tech munitions has worn  
off, although 90 percent of NATO strikes are precision-guided 
compared to 10 percent in the Gulf War. The U.S. and international 
public is bombarded instead with images of more than 1 million 
refugees running for their lives from Serb forces, and of civilian 
carnage when NATO bombs and missiles go astray. 
</P>
<P>
	``The story is of massive human suffering and of a conflict more  
difficult than we imagined,'' Lichter said. 
</P>
<P>
	During the six-week Gulf War, the networks showed 594 allied  
gunfight pictures, nearly five per night each for ABC, CBS and NBC, 
Lichter said. 
</P>
<P>
	The center hasn't compiled comparable figures for NATO  
airstrikes, but Lichter said his news watchers report little TV use 
of Pentagon gun-camera footage and NATO satellite photos of bomb 
damage. 
</P>
<P>
	The networks and cable news channels, like print reporters, have  
been constrained in directly covering bomb damage from NATO strikes 
since the Serbs have barred international journalists from Kosovo. 
Yugoslav authorities also limit the movement of correspondents in 
Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like we can go around and gather the material we  
want,'' said ABC spokeswoman Eileen Murphy. ``It's the human face 
of this conflict that people are interested in and that's where we 
have the ability to do our own reporting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	CNN carries many Pentagon and NATO briefings live, but most of  
its reporting also focuses on the human angle. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've done a good job of reporting what's going on, but the  
refugee stuff is incredibly compelling,'' said CNN spokesman David 
Bittler. 
</P>
<P>
	One opinion poll suggests few Americans are paying attention to  
the military effects of NATO's attacks. Just under one in 10 people 
said they were most interested in news of damage to Serb targets, 
according to a poll by the Pew Research Center for the People &AMP; the 
Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked what has captured their attention most, more than  
one-third said the March 31 capture of three American soldiers near 
the Macedonia-Yugoslav border. About three in 10 said refugees 
leaving Kosovo, the Serbian province under attack by Yugoslav 
forces. One-fourth said the ethnic Albanian victims themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	The telephone poll of 1,000 Americans was taken April 15-18. It  
has a margin of error of plus or minus 3.5 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Pentagon shots show allied bombs and missiles destroying  
Serb supply lines into Kosovo, such as roads, rail lines and 
bridges. Others show NATO hitting fuel and arms depots, sometimes 
with scores of cluster bombs exploding like Fourth of July 
fireworks. The Pentagon also has shown footage of allied jets 
coming under Serb anti-aircraft fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Zorthian, chief U.S. military spokesman from 1964 through  
1968 during the Vietnam War, said the Pentagon must be sensitive in 
releasing attack footage. Strikes against buildings -- including 
Serb political party headquarters, Milosevic's homes and state-run 
TV broadcast centers -- raise the ugly specter of NATO targeting 
civilians. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you see too much of the Yugoslavia infrastructure being  
blown up, people may say it's too much,'' Zorthian said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
