<DOCNO> APW19990501.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 20:12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pit Crew Chief Killed at Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILLIAMS TOWNSHIP, Mich. (AP) -- Timothy Vouaux, a pit crew chief  
working at the Tri-City Motor Speedway, was killed when two cars 
collided during a race and spun into the guardrail where he was 
standing, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Vouaux, 42, of Saginaw, Mich., was the first person to die at  
the Bay County racetrack since it reopened in May 1996 after being 
closed for two years. 
</P>
<P>
	He died in surgery Saturday morning, Michigan State Trooper  
Yvonne Brantley said. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident, which occurred about 11 p.m. Friday, is still  
under investigation, Brantley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Friends and family say Vouaux was a fan and participant in car  
racing for 20 years. Don Riley, who had known Vouaux for 30 years, 
said Vouaux was a good racer, but had an avid interest in mechanics 
and switched to working on pit crews himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was very serious,'' Riley said. ``He didn't like conflicts  
that didn't make sense. In racing and whatever, he always wanted to 
go forward. He didn't want things holding anybody back that were 
just personal matters. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was truly fantastic, a wonderful person.''  
</P>
<P>
	Vouaux worked as a maintenance mechanic at the Saginaw  
Wastewater Treatment Plant. He and his wife have 6-year-old 
triplets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990501.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 08:31:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Archdiocese Builds Mortuaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Archdiocese of Los Angeles bypassed local  
mortuaries and contracted with a for-profit company to build 
funeral homes at tax-exempt church cemeteries that will provide 
one-stop embalming, casketing, chapel service and burial. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, which will make the nation's largest Roman Catholic  
archdiocese only the second to put mortuaries on church property, 
has prompted complaints of unfair competition from angry funeral 
directors, some of whom have served the archdiocese for more than a 
century. 
</P>
<P>
	The archdiocese, which has a flock of 3.6 million, made a deal  
with mortuary consolidator Stewart Enterprises Inc. in 1998 to 
build funeral homes at six of the 11 tax-exempt, consecrated 
graveyards it operates in Southern California and at two it runs in 
the Tucson, Ariz., diocese. 
</P>
<P>
	Archdiocese and Stewart officials refused to discuss the value  
of the deal or how much the church will likely earn. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal has angered rivals, who contend the church's prestige  
and nonprofit status put them at a distinct disadvantage. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's wrong. The church should not engage in competition with  
private enterprise,'' says John J. Horan, operator of five 
mortuaries in Denver, the only other U.S. archdiocese with a 
mortuary on its property. The Denver archdiocese owns its funeral 
home outright. 
</P>
<P>
	``Imagine how persuasive the church can be,'' Horan says. ``It's  
kind of hard to fight a multimillion-dollar industry like the 
church.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Horan says his funerals dropped from 800 a year to about 500  
when the Catholic mortuary opened there. At least one traditionally 
Catholic funeral home went out of business. Others, like Horan, 
diversified to serve other faiths and denominations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We took all our eggs out of the Catholic basket,'' he says.  
</P>
<P>
	The 100-odd Los Angeles-area mortuaries were not allowed to bid  
for the archdiocese cemetery work, and the archdiocese acknowledges 
some are angry over a slight that they believe discounts their 
years of service. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know there are people less than happy, but they are already  
in competition with other mortuaries. It just provides another 
option,'' says archdiocese spokesman Gregory Coiro. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart Enterprises, based in New Orleans, owns and operates 378  
mortuaries and 127 cemeteries in 23 states, Puerto Rico and six 
other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart is leasing the cemetery land from the church and will  
pay property and business taxes, Coiro says. The funeral home will 
bear the cemetery name and Stewart won't appear on signs. 
</P>
<P>
	The archdiocese insists money is not the issue. Coiro declined  
to discuss the archdiocese's budget but called its finances ``quite 
sound.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Expanding the church's role in the funeral business seems to be  
an idea gaining momentum. In its ``A Vision for the Millennium'' 
decree, the Des Plaines, Ill.-based National Catholic Cemetery 
Conference urged Catholic cemeteries to consider operating funeral 
homes. 
</P>
<P>
	``To emphasize church teachings and to promote the universal  
application of the Order of Christian Funerals, the Catholic 
cemetery may consider operating its own funeral homes,'' the 
conference decree said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some rivals dismiss the religious justification.  
</P>
<P>
	``The motivation of the church leaders can be found far closer  
to Earth than to heaven: It will be a moneymaker,'' the Funeral 
Monitor, an industry watchdog newsletter based in Tiburon, Calif., 
said recently. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillip Bagues III's East Los Angeles funeral home is a mile  
from the archdiocese-owned Calvary Cemetery, where the first 
Stewart-run mortuary opens in September. He says he sends families 
to Calvary to buy cemetery lots and commonly, within a week, they 
receive calls from Stewart salespeople. 
</P>
<P>
	``They say they are the church, and the family thinks they are  
going to the church, not Stewart,'' Bagues says. 
</P>
<P>
	He predicts trouble for the new Calvary mortuary. Stewart rates  
for a funeral run twice as much -- $4,000 compared to $2,000, he 
asserts. ``People are shopping around now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Randy Stricklin, coordinator for Stewart's Catholic mortuary  
operations, refused to comment on the company's prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard R. Gutierrez, whose Guerra-Gutierrez Mortuary is three  
miles from Calvary, says he'll fight the church-affiliated 
competition with better service and prices and a new $2 million 
facility. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to compete aggressively,'' he says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
