<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Atlanta Opens Olympic Recordbook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- There was no evidence of bribery -- but plenty of  
fawning over IOC members by city officials -- when Atlanta Olympics 
record were opened to the public for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine boxes of records released -- a mere fraction of the  
total -- showed no evidence of the problems that have tarnished Salt 
Lake City's Olympic bid, but they did detail Atlanta's 
take-no-prisoners strategy to win over IOC members prior to the 
1990 vote giving the city the 1996 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The boxes included scores of thank-you notes, fund-raising  
letters, newspaper articles and marketing plans, including one that 
warned Atlanta leaders that ``lobbying the 90-member IOC voting 
bloc is tricky business, not unlike walking through a minefield at 
midnight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The records show that Atlanta Olympics chief Billy Payne and his  
helpers exhaustively researched each IOC member's background, 
family and hobbies. They lured them to the city several times 
before the 1990 vote, then showered them with gifts, fine food, 
entertainment and deluxe accommodations. 
</P>
<P>
	When IOC members stayed at a private home in Atlanta, Payne  
instructed the hosts to ``plan major sports and cultural events. 
Leave no stone unturned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After one visit in 1989, Payne instructed the wives of the host  
families to correspond with their visiting IOC member every other 
month and he suggested topics to include in their letters. 
</P>
<P>
	While bid cities are allowed to fly IOC members to their city  
first-class, the records showed just how costly that can be. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, Payne's group spent $11,120 just to fly the Swedish  
IOC delegate and his wife to Atlanta for a lobbying event five 
months before the 1990 vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation, which is embroiled in  
a legal fight to keep some bid records sealed, voluntarily opened 
the nine boxes of documents. 
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta History Center, which has stored the records since  
1997, gave reporters limited periods of time to look at the records 
Friday. The Associated Press had the opportunity to look at only 
five of the nine boxes. 
</P>
<P>
	The records, of which there are a total of 4,000 boxes, are at  
the center of a legal dispute over whether the public should be 
allowed to view documents detailing Atlanta's bid for the games. 
</P>
<P>
	The athletics foundation was created by Payne in 1987 to bid for  
the Olympics. The nonprofit group claims the documents are the 
property of a group of private citizens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
