<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paper: Milosevic Proposes Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic  
acknowledged that ``bad things happened'' in Kosovo and offered a 
plan to end the military conflict, according to an interview 
published today. 
</P>
<P>
	In the interview with The Washington Times, Milosevic called for  
the end to all military activities and the simultaneous withdrawal 
of 90,000 Yugoslav forces from Kosovo and of NATO forces from the 
surrounding area. His plan also would include a lightly armed U.N. 
peacekeeping mission that would include Russian forces. 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic, who met with a Washington Times editor in Belgrade on  
Thursday outlined what he called a six-point peace plan. The 
proposal also called for the return of all refugees, peace talks 
with moderate political leaders in Kosovo and an economic recovery 
plan for Serbia, Kosovo and Montenegro. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration was skeptical of any offers from  
Belgrade and White House spokesman Joe Lockhart called Milosevic's 
proposals ``clearly inadequate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said ``we are not anywhere  
near a serious peace proposal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In conceding that ``bad things'' happened in Kosovo, Milosevic  
blamed them on undisciplined paramilitary troops, some of whom have 
been punished. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not angels,'' he said in the interview. ``Nor are we  
the devils you have made us out to be. Our regular forces are 
highly disciplined. The paramilitary irregular forces are a 
different story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic, speaking in English, reiterated his opposition to any  
kind of NATO peacekeeping mission in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he was prepared to face more bombing, he said that  
``one day is too much'' but he said his forces would never 
surrender. 
</P>
<P>
	``We Serbs are as one on this life-and-death issue of national  
honor and sovereignty,'' he told the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
