<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NHL Playoff Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	What home-ice advantage?  
</P>
<P>
	It certainly hasn't meant anything so far in the NHL playoff  
series between the San Jose Sharks and Colorado Avalanche. 
</P>
<P>
	For the fourth time in four games, the road team won as the  
Sharks beat the Avalanche 7-3 Friday night to tie their Western 
Conference series at two games apiece. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel really good about our situation now,'' Vincent  
Damphousse said after scoring two short-handed goals. ``... We know 
we're going back to San Jose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That won't come until Monday night. The teams will play Game 5  
tonight in Denver, with the schedule reconfigured because of the 
shootings at a suburban high school. 
</P>
<P>
	``(A 2-2 series is) a lot better than coming in here two down,''  
Damphousse said. ``Our key now is to win the game (tonight) and 
have a chance to win at home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, it was New Jersey 4, Pittsburgh 3; Toronto 2,  
Philadelphia 1 in overtime; Boston 4, Carolina 3 in double 
overtime; and St. Louis 2, Phoenix 1 in overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	The San Jose-Colorado game is the only playoff game on tap  
tonight. On Sunday, it's New Jersey at Pittsburgh, Toronto at 
Philadelphia, Carolina at Boston and Phoenix at St. Louis. The 
Devils, Maple Leafs, Bruins and Coyotes have 3-2 leads. 
</P>
<P>
	Damphousse scored two short-handed goals in the third period as  
the Sharks guaranteed themselves another home playoff game. 
</P>
<P>
	Alex Korolyuk had a goal and two assists for the Sharks, who  
trailed 2-0 midway through the second period but scored the game's 
final four goals -- all coming within a 10:07 span of the third 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Vernon finished with 32 saves for San Jose. Patrick Roy  
stopped 18 of 24 shots before being pulled late in the final 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got embarrassed,'' Colorado captain Joe Sakic said. ``We  
can't worry about what's happened in the past. We have the 
best-of-3 and two games at home. We have to make sure we take 
advantage of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
                        *Devils 4, Penguins 3    	
</P>
<P>
	Petr Sykora scored on rebound early in the third period, and New  
Jersey overcame a 13-second lapse to beat visiting Pittsburgh 
without Jaromir Jagr. 
</P>
<P>
	The Devils, who also got two goals from Randy McKay, can wrap up  
the best-of-7 series by winning either Game 6 at Pittsburgh on 
Sunday or, if necessary, Game 7 at home on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jagr missed his fourth straight game with a groin injury, and  
the Penguins only managed 17 shots without him. The NHL's leading 
scorer also didn't sound optimistic that he would be able to play 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
                      *Maple Leafs 2, Flyers 1, OT    	
</P>
<P>
	Yanic Perreault scored 11:51 into overtime as Toronto won at  
home and moved within a victory of the second round. 
</P>
<P>
	Perreault's backhander eluded goalie John Vanbiesbrouck after  
the Flyers' Keith Jones and the Leafs' Dimitri Yushkevich exchanged 
first-period goals. The Flyers have lost seven straight playoff 
overtime games since an OT win in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
                     *Bruins 4, Hurricanes 3, 2OT    	
</P>
<P>
	Anson Carter scored on a backhander with 5:15 left in the second  
overtime as Boston won at Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bruins came into the second OT holding a 47-31 lead in  
shots, and Carter's breakaway goal on Carolina's Arturs Irbe was 
Boston's 52nd shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Thornton and Ray Bourque assisted on Carter's game-winner in  
the longest game in Carolina franchise history. 
</P>
<P>
                        *Blues 2, Coyotes 1, OT    	
</P>
<P>
	Al MacInnis tied the game with a goal in the third period, and  
Scott Young scored 5:43 into overtime as St. Louis staved off 
elimination at Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blues will go into Game 6 with momentum after outshooting  
Phoenix 43-27 and outskating the Coyotes throughout the second 
overtime game of the series. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas Drake scored his fourth playoff goal on a Phoenix power  
play in the second period, but Grant Fuhr handled 26 other shots 
for his 88th playoff victory, which tied him with Billy Smith for 
second in NHL history. Colorado's Patrick Roy leads with 101 wins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
