<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 16:52:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baffert Falls Short in Derby Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Bob Baffert was in his lucky box, wearing  
his lucky tie. He even met Muhammad Ali in the paddock before 
Saturday's 125th Kentucky Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	But when it came time to deliver the knockout that would give  
Baffert a record third straight Derby win, his three entries came 
up short. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Timber was fourth, the filly Excellent Meeting fifth and  
General Challenge 11th, all behind the race's winner, the D. Wayne 
Lukas-trained Charismatic. 
</P>
<P>
	None ever challenged for the lead, with both Excellent Meeting  
and Prime Timber coming from back in the pack in the final 
quarter-mile of the race. 
</P>
<P>
	General Challenge raced in traffic throughout, never moving  
closer to the lead than seventh. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm disappointed we did not get a chance to run,'' Baffert  
said. ``I knew we were dead in the first turn. General Challenge 
was getting jerked around all over the place. This race is won on 
the first turn.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All week long at Churchill Downs, the white-haired Baffert, with  
his distinctive dark glasses, was the center of attention. He had 
come in second by a nose in 1996 with Cavonnier, then won in 1997 
and 1998 with Silver Charm and Real Quiet. 
</P>
<P>
	Finishing out of the money was a new experience after the last  
three years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know how to act,'' Baffert said. ``We're sort of lost  
souls. We didn't have any luck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There were too many horses and too much traffic,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Coming into Derby week, Baffert looked well-positioned to win  
the Derby for the third year in a row. He brought a stable to 
Kentucky that included the top two finishers in the Santa Anita 
Derby, General Challenge and Prime Timber, and two fillies believed 
by many to be the equal of any 3-year-old colts in the land, 
Excellent Meeting and Silverbulletday. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert stuck by an early decision to run Silverbulletday in  
Friday's Kentucky Oaks, but waited until Friday to announce he 
would run Excellent Meeting in the Derby, and not the Oaks. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday then won the Oaks easily, giving Baffert a shot  
at being the first trainer to train an Oaks and Derby winner in the 
same year since Ben A. Jones in 1952. 
</P>
<P>
	He was ready for the big day, with his blue tie for luck and  
sitting with Prime Timber owners Mr. and Mrs. Aaron Jones in the 
same box where he sat for the wins by Real Quiet and Silver Charm. 
</P>
<P>
	The Excellent Meeting-General Challenge joint entry, owned by  
Mr. and Mrs. John Mabee, ended up going off as the 9-2 favorite, 
but became the 20th straight Derby favorite to fail to win the 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997 and 1998, Silver Charm and Real Quiet won the first two  
legs of the Triple Crown for Baffert, then came up short in the 
Belmont Stakes. In his post-Derby disappointment, Baffert was able 
to find a silver lining at not winning. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now I don't have to worry about the Triple Crown this year,''  
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
