<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> POW Families Grateful for Jackson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Vivian Ramirez smiled broadly as she talked  
about watching a videotape of her son, Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, 
standing with his arm around the Rev. Jesse Jackson in war-torn 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt very emotional. ... I could've gone in there and just  
hugged him,'' she said Friday after viewing the tape of Jackson's 
visit with Ramirez and two other U.S. soldiers being held prisoner. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez, 24, Christopher Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich., and  
Steven Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas, were captured while 
patrolling the Yugoslavia-Macedonia border on March 31, seven days 
after NATO launched its bombing campaign in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	The three were in good health, Jackson said. They had not been  
allowed to meet with any Westerners until a visit by International 
Red Cross officials this week. 
</P>
<P>
	In the video approved by Serb censors, Stone appears tired, and  
his eyes well with tears as he sends his love to his wife, Tricia, 
and 4-year-old son, Ryan. He says a fading bruise on hi forehead is 
``a mark from our capture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I am very happy and relieved that he looks well,'' Mrs. Stone  
said. ``I'm very hopeful that more positive things will come out of 
this. I pray every day and night for the safe return of Chris, 
Andrew and Steven.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though thin, Ramirez appears healthier compared with the first  
video released by Yugoslav authorities just after his capture when 
all three soldiers had battered faces, his mother said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was worse before when I didn't hear anything, just the  
pictures they were showing from early times. That was unbearable,'' 
Mrs. Ramirez said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she didn't know if Jackson's efforts would help speed  
the release of her son. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, he will. Hopefully, I pray he will,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	The mother and her daughter sent Ramirez a cassette with a taped  
message. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just told him that I loved him very much, I told him to take  
care, not to worry, that we were doing all we could to bring him 
back home,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
