<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Attends Press Dinner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After a year in which he was impeached and his  
life's most intimate moments were exposed to the public, a night 
out with the White House press corps wouldn't seem to be President 
Clinton's ideal evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday evening, though, Clinton put aside any lingering  
bitterness and cracked a few jokes at the annual White House 
Correspondents Association dinner at a Washington hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton showed up late enough to miss the presentation of an  
award to Newsweek's Michael Isikoff, a reporter who dedicated the 
past year to unearthing the Monica Lewinsky scandal. Instead, the 
president came in time to hear the jokes of MSNBC anchor Brian 
Williams, master of ceremonies for the dinner. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams poked fun at Washington's media elite, telling the  
audience that The Washington Post was late to the event because it 
has been ``going out to dinner on the same story since 1974,'' a 
reference to its breaking much of the Watergate scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams also took shots at political leaders, frequently  
mocking Vice President Al Gore for his claim that he invented the 
Internet. Clinton took the podium and responded, saying that Gore, 
who attended the Kentucky Derby on Saturday, never claimed he sired 
the winning horse. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton then poked fun at the press, telling the crowd that  
veteran reporter Helen Thomas of United Press International was 
upset at a proposed move in the White House briefing room because 
she remembered the last time it moved -- when the capital changed 
from Philadelphia to Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The president, who later spoke seriously about the situation in  
Kosovo, joked with the assembled media about war coverage. He asked 
them to imagine the effects the 24-hour media would have had on 
other wars. The sub-headline on a story about President Lincoln's 
Gettysburg Address? President ``does not offer exit strategy.'' How 
about Gen. Douglas MacArthur's promise to return to the 
Philippines? MacArthur ``does not set clear timetable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, the president and the dinner audience were entertained by  
singer Aretha Franklin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
