<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 16:05:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wichita St. Pitcher Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WICHITA, Kan. (AP) -- Wichita State's Ben Christensen, who hit an  
opposing player with a warmup pitch last week, was suspended for 
the rest of the season on Friday by the Missouri Valley Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitching coach Brent Kemnitz also was suspended from game day  
participation for the remainder of the regular season and any 
postseason games involving the University of Evansville. 
</P>
<P>
	Christensen hit Evansville's Anthony Molina in the head with a  
warmup pitch before the game on April 23. Molina was reported to be 
at least 15 feet from home plate when he was hit. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspension keeps Christensen out for the remainder of the  
1999 regular season, conference tournament and the NCAA tournament. 
He will be allowed to continue as a member of the team and to 
participate in practices and non-game activities. 
</P>
<P>
	Kemnitz will be allowed to resume his coaching duties during the  
conference postseason tournament, and will be allowed to practice 
with the team and perform other coaching duties during his 
suspension. 
</P>
<P>
	Wichita State issued a brief statement Friday saying the  
university would not appeal the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``After intensive and exhaustive discussions with  
representatives of the Missouri Valley Conference during the past 
week, the University has made this decision not to appeal in an 
attempt to move forward and seek closure,'' athletic director Bill 
Belknap said. 
</P>
<P>
	The MVC ruling did not specifically address the reasons the  
pitching coach was included in the suspension, but Kemnitz 
reportedly teaches his pitchers to brush back on-deck batters who 
stand too close to the plate. 
</P>
<P>
	Molina sustained a one-inch gash above his left eye, which is  
swollen shut -- and he has expressed fears he may have permanent 
damage to his sight. The beaning also caused three small fractures 
in Molina's cheekbone. 
</P>
<P>
	``More than anything, we are certainly hoping that Anthony  
Molina's recovery is quick and complete,'' Missouri Valley 
Conference commissioner Doug Elgin said in a release. ``We are 
truly sorry for all parties involved that the injury occurred.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Belknap apologized on behalf of Wichita State to Molina, his  
family and coach and to the University of Evansville. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are sincerely sorry that this unintentional, but  
regrettable, accident occurred,'' he said. ``We send our best 
wishes for full and complete recovery to Anthony Molina.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Christensen, who was immediately ejected from the game by home  
plate umpire Gary Mitchell, received an automatic four-game 
suspension per NCAA rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the MVC nor Wichita State would comment beyond the brief  
statements. Christensen could not be reached for comment Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	After last Friday's game, Christensen said he meant the pitch to  
be only a warning and that he didn't mean to hit Molina. Kemnitz 
said at the time he teaches brushback pitches but has never told a 
pitcher to hit a batter. 
</P>
<P>
	Christensen, a junior right-hander, leads the Shockers, ranked  
seventh in the Collegiate Baseball poll, with a 9-1 record. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
