<DOCNO> APW19990501.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 14:22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Why did Pats' Owner Spurn Conn.? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A day after New England Patriots owner Bob Kraft  
spurned a $380 million stadium offer in Connecticut for a deal in 
Massachusetts that will cost him millions, an obvious question 
remained. 
</P>
<P>
	What was Kraft thinking?  
</P>
<P>
	The answer, according to local business leaders and experts,  
involves a mix of loyalty to his home state and fears the 
Connecticut deal could turn into a financial nightmare. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's both, no question,'' said Paul Kirk, who led a group of  
businessmen in a last-second push to keep the team in 
Massachusetts. 
</P>
<P>
	Once doubts surfaced about a 2002 deadline for a Hartford  
stadium opening, Kraft faced the possibility of long, costly delays 
on a project he didn't control, Kirk said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Massachusetts' $70 million plan allows Kraft to take out a  
loan he essentially doesn't have to pay back for construction on 
land he owns in his home state. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a matter of betting on a sure thing or taking a risk for  
a bigger jackpot, according to political consultant Michael 
Goldman. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wasn't willing to take the risk,'' Goldman said.  
</P>
<P>
	Kraft was not available for comment Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
	Signs that Kraft's tentative deal with Connecticut was on shaky  
ground emerged over the last weeks. And hours before the deal was 
called off, Connecticut Gov. John Rowland said the state might not 
have the stadium completed by 2002 -- the deadline set by Kraft. 
</P>
<P>
	Andy Zimbalist, a sports economist at Smith College, said the  
recent troubles might have shown Kraft the Connecticut plan wasn't 
as sweet as it looked. 
</P>
<P>
	Delays with cleanup at the Hartford waterfront site proposed for  
the stadium could have been unpredictably long and costly, despite 
Rowland's projection for a 2003 opening, he said. Kraft would have 
missed a projected $100 million in annual revenue for each year 
missed in Hartford, according to Zimbalist. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, Kraft would have presided over a lame-duck team  
with diminishing profitability in Foxboro. 
</P>
<P>
	Zimbalist added that the National Football League was likely to  
pursue a new franchise for Boston, the country's sixth-largest 
media market. That would have eroded an already weakened fan base, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	And given NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue's public advocacy of a  
new Massachusetts home for the Patriots, Kirk said he doubted that 
the league would have approved the move to Hartford. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, Kraft was thinking about long-term benefits, rather  
than short-term gain, Massachusetts House Speaker Thomas Finneran 
said. He compared the hefty Connecticut deal to ``extra caffeine in 
your coffee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``In the end it might not prove to be helpful,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	While Connecticut's plan was running into problems,  
Massachusetts presented a $70 million package for infrastructure 
improvements. Though Kraft would have to pay for a new stadium 
himself, he can take advantage of a two-month-old NFL 
stadium-financing provision called G-3. 
</P>
<P>
	The provision could give Kraft league financing for up to half  
of the estimated $250 million cost of a new stadium. But the league 
forgives repayment of the entire principle if Kraft doesn't sell 
the Patriots for 10 years after the stadium is finished. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, league rules permit the one-third share of luxury  
seat revenues -- normally given to visiting NFL teams -- to be used 
for stadium construction. In the end, Kraft's bottom line won't be 
significantly damaged. 
</P>
<P>
	Finneran, who has opposed former stadium plans, said he expects  
the legislature to approve the stadium plan quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	Kraft also stands to benefit for what Kirk called the ``psychic  
income'' from his decision to stay in the state, which he explained 
as the goodwill Kraft will reap from fans happy they stayed put. 
</P>
<P>
	Political consultant Charley Manning said Kraft will be  
``revered'' for his decision to reject a possible short-term gain. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this day and age, it's almost a heroic gesture to leave the  
money on the table,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Zimbalist said it should be clear that if Connecticut's deal  
hadn't run into problems, Kraft would have left his home state in a 
flash. 
</P>
<P>
	``The notion that he was engaging in some sort of active  
self-sacrifice in order to remain in Boston is, in my view, 
preposterous,'' he said. ``Clearly he was ready to run to the 
riches if he was able to.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
