<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ray Wins Pole at Charlotte </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- Maybe nothing can keep a Team Menard car  
from winning the pole for the VisionAire 500. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Ray captured the top starting spot for tonight's race by  
running the fastest lap ever recorded at Lowe's Motor Speedway at 
Charlotte. It marked the third time in the 3-year history of the 
VisionAire 500 that a Team Menard driver won the pole, but this one 
was anything but routine. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were lucky enough to reach under the hat and find the  
rabbit,'' Ray said after he overcame several potential problems 
before and during Friday night's qualifying run. 
</P>
<P>
	It started in technical inspection before time trials, when Pep  
Boys Indy Racing League inspectors failed Ray's Dallara Aurora 
because of a problem with its ground clearance. According to Ray, 
the machine's ground clearance was too low by one-hundredth of an 
inch. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was nothing that gave us a technical advantage,'' Ray said,  
``but it didn't comply, so we had to adjust it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL's penalty was to limit Ray to just one qualifying lap  
instead of two like everyone else. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray's problems still weren't finished, however.  
</P>
<P>
	``We were in such a hurry to get going after the second  
inspection that we forgot to hook up the radio,'' he said. ``I had 
absolutely no idea how fast I was going, but I knew I only had one 
lap to do it. I just tried to squeeze every little bit I could out 
of the race car.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That turned out to be enough. Ray recorded a speed of 222.039  
mph, shattering the track record of 220.498 set one year ago by 
Tony Stewart, the driver Ray succeeded at Team Menard. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Sharp and Scott Goodyear, the series points leader after  
two of 11 races, both broke the track record as well in the lone 
round of qualifying. Sharp had a 221.239 and Goodyear a 221.076 on 
a cool evening when rain delayed qualifying and high winds made it 
more difficult on the 1.5-mile, high-banked trioval. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very hard to be completely consistent,'' Goodyear said.  
``You feel like you're being moved around the track a whole lot. It 
feels like it can move you as much as a half car-length to either 
side, and that's certainly not something that would be good in the 
race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Qualifying began an hour late because of delays caused by four  
days of often heavy rains in the region. Thursday's practice 
sessions were wiped out by the storms, and there originally was 
some thought that Friday's lone scheduled round of time trials 
would also become a casualty. 
</P>
<P>
	Since this is the circuit's first stop of the year at a  
high-banked superspeedway, IRL officials considered eliminating 
qualifying in favor of practice time to help the teams adjust to 
the speeds. Track officials, however, employed some unique methods 
to salvage a practice session and still leave enough time for 
qualifying. 
</P>
<P>
	Once it became apparent that the water seepage and runoff were  
especially heavy in the fourth turn, the speedway dispatched crews 
to the area to seek a two-pronged solution. Workers drilled 
2-foot-deep holes into the track and used heavy-duty concrete saws 
to cut small grooves that channeled the water off the 24-degree 
banking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
