<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Heavyweight Champ McCall Freed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARTINSVILLE, Va. (AP) -- Former heavyweight boxing champion  
Oliver McCall was released from jail Saturday after serving a 
little more than half of a one-year jail sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel great,'' McCall, 35, said in a telephone interview  
after his release. ``I want to get ready to fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCall, who was in jail for resisting arrest and assaulting a  
law enforcement officer, blames repeated problems with the law on 
an addiction to cocaine. A Martinsville judge decided that McCall 
could be released as long as he stays in a drug rehabilitation 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	``I ain't going to have no problems,'' McCall said Saturday.  
``I'm drug free and I'm going to stay that way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCall and his lawyer plan to go to an Ohio training center to  
begin training. 
</P>
<P>
	McCall said promoter Don King is arranging for him to return to  
the ring in Mississippi in June. He said he doesn't yet know who 
he'll face. 
</P>
<P>
	The fighter knocked out Lennox Lewis for the WBC title in  
September 1994, then defended the title against Larry Holmes in 
1995. He then lost his belt to Frank Bruno in a 12-round decision. 
</P>
<P>
	He fought Lewis again on Feb. 8, 1997 for the vacant WBC title.  
It was stopped after four rounds and awarded to Lewis when a 
sobbing McCall refused to fight. 
</P>
<P>
	McCall was arrested in Martinsville last Oct. 14, convicted Dec.  
18 and sentenced to one year in jail and 10 years probation. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Circuit Judge Charles Stone decided to release  
McCall after King testified that he would help him rededicate his 
life to being a productive citizen. 
</P>
<P>
	Stone expressed reservations about the release, and ordered that  
the fighter submit to random drug testing three times every two 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have the best of intentions, when you've been caught and  
you are in jail and you're away from the (drugs),'' Stone said at 
the time. ``... But when you get out there, that all flies out the 
window and all you want to do is get cocaine. I've seen it happen 
again and again.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
