<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Milosevic To Free Three U.S. POWs  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has  
agreed to hand three American prisoners over Sunday to the Rev. 
Jesse Jackson, who will escort them to freedom in Croatia. 
Milosevic's action could be a genuine peace move or a clever 
end-run around the White House to exploit congressional doubts 
about the handling of the crisis with Yugoslavia. Jackson will also 
carry a letter from Milosevic to President Clinton outlining steps 
to stop the conflict. Jackson said it includes a stunning offer by 
Milosevic to meet face-to-face with Clinton ``and to take this 
matter to resolution through negotiations.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Dozens Said Killed in NATO Strike  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A NATO missile struck a civilian bus  
crossing a bridge in Yugoslavia today, killing dozens of people, 
news reports and witnesses said. The private Beta news agency 
reported 60 people dead while the state-run Tanjug agency said 40 
people had been killed. Pentagon officials said they could not 
confirm the reports, and NATO had no immediate comment on the 
attack. In another attack reported by Tanjug, five people were 
killed today when a NATO missile struck Prizren, Kosovo's second 
largest city. 

</P>
<P>
	Ark. Boat Accident Claims 11 Lives  
</P>
<P>
	HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) -- Eleven people were killed today when an  
amphibious tourist boat sank. Passengers aboard the open-air, World 
War II-vintage boat panicked and scrambled for life preservers as 
it took on water and sank suddenly on Lake Hamilton near this 
popular tourist town, the city manager said. The dead included 
three children, including a young girl. The driver of the boat was 
among the survivors. Twenty people were on board and none were 
wearing life preservers, officials said. The boat sank in one or 
two minutes as it cruised less than a mile offshore, said City 
Manager Kent Myers and witnesses. 

</P>
<P>
	Heston Defends NRA  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Charlton Heston today said his National Rifle  
Association wasn't the villain in the Columbine High School 
massacre. While a larger-than-expected crowd came to the gun 
lobby's annual meeting, thousands of opponents circled the meeting 
site, some carrying signs that read ``Shame on the NRA'' and ``NRA, 
Pusher of Child Killer Machines.'' The nation's largest group of 
gun owners cut the meeting from three days to one and eliminated a 
gun exhibit but refused to cancel it altogether, despite requests 
to do so from Mayor Wellington Webb and other local officials. 

</P>
<P>
	Heat Wave Shuts Down India Schools  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Worried about a heat wave that has  
killed 110 people in India, authorities today ordered schools in 
the capital to close immediately, advancing the annual summer 
vacation by two weeks. Schools in India are not air-conditioned, 
and many children must walk long distances from home. The Weather 
Office in New Delhi said the temperature soared to 117 degrees in 
Hissar, a town in Haryana state that borders the capital. 

</P>
<P>
	Panama Election Focuses on Canal  
</P>
<P>
	PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) -- Panamanians see tomorrow's  
presidential election as a chance to prove to the world they are 
ready to take over the Panama Canal, 10 years after U.S. forces 
threw out their military ruler. Candidates running in the second 
presidential vote since the 1989 invasion have loaded their 
discourse with assurances they will see that the canal remains 
above politics and corruption. Polls show Martin Torrijos and 
Mireya Moscoso in a statistical dead heat. The Canal Treaties, 
signed in 1977, commit the United States to handing over the canal 
on Dec. 31. 

</P>
<P>
	China Opens Garden Show  
</P>
<P>
	KUNMING, China (AP) -- With a release of pigeons and balloons,  
China opened what it said was the world's biggest garden show 
today, part of an ambitious effort to promote its impoverished 
southwest as a center for trade and tourism. Exhibitors from 68 
countries and each of China's 33 provinces are displaying flowers 
and architecture on a sprawling site in the wooded hills outside 
Kunming, capital of Yunnan province and known for its pleasant, 
tropical climate. President Jiang Zemin presided at an opening 
ceremony before hundreds of spectators. 

</P>
<P>
	Charismatic Wins Kentucky Derby  
</P>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Charismatic, a 30-1 shot, won the 125th  
Kentucky Derby today. The win gave trainer D. Wayne Lukas his third 
victory of the 1990s. Charismatic, ridden by Chris Antley, held off 
Menifee, with Lukas' other starter, Cat Thief, third. It was the 
fourth Derby victory overall for Lukas, who was voted into the Hall 
of Fame on Tuesday. Lukas now is one of three trainers to win at 
least four Derbys. Bob Baffert's three starters finished out of the 
money, nullifying the trainer's bid to become the first person to 
win three straight Derbys. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
</P>
</TEXT>
