<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Ref Might Have Tax Case Dropped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Tax-evasion charges against an NBA referee  
should be dropped because a grand jury operated improperly, a 
federal judge said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Magistrate Judge David Baker issued his recommendation  
Friday, temporarily halting the trial of Blane Reichelt. Jury 
selection was to begin Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Two grand juries heard evidence in the case against Reichelt,  
but only the second grand jury voted to indict him. In his report, 
Baker said the second grand jury failed to receive transcripts 
presented to the first grand jury as required by law. 
</P>
<P>
	``The grand jury's independence is subject to grave doubt,''  
Baker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors and defense attorneys declined comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Reichelt, an 18-year veteran of the NBA, was one of 12 referees  
who were investigated by the Internal Revenue Service in 
``Operation Slam Dunk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The officials were charged with exchanging first-class airline  
tickets provided by the league for coach tickets and pocketing the 
difference without reporting the extra income on their taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1989, Reichelt, of Melbourne, Fla., failed to report $13,680  
in taxable income, the indictment against him said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Patricia Fawsett was expected to rule on  
Baker's recommendation next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten of the referees were charged in the IRS investigation  
pleaded guilty. They were sentenced to probation or short periods 
of house arrest and ordered to pay the taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	One referee, Steve Javie, was acquitted by a jury in  
Philadelphia in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
