<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ideal Towne Wins Berry's Creek Pace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Ideal Towne charged down the middle  
of the track to win a battle of late-pacing colts and captured the 
$300,000 Berry's Creek pace at the Meadowlands on Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	In giving driver Mike Lachance his third win in this race, Ideal  
Towne paced the mile for 3-year-olds in 1:52 and got to the wire 
three-quarters of a length ahead of The Paper Wazoo, who made a 
late move along the rail with Luc Ouellette. 
</P>
<P>
	Homespun Fun finished third, another head back and a nose in  
front of heavy favorite Union Guy, who also made a run from the 
back of the pack, but even further outside Ideal Towne. 
</P>
<P>
	Ideal Towne, who finished second in his elimination for this  
race last week, returned $9.40, $4.80 and $4 in winning for the 
first time in three starts this year. The Illinois-bred son of 
Ideal Society earned $150,000 in doubling his lifetime earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chris Ryder-trained colt earned $143,500 in winning five of  
seven starts last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Breaking from the No. 5 post, Lachance and Ideal Towne took  
advantage of the fact that the speed horses in the race had outside 
posts. That meant they could sit back and let those horses rush out 
to the lead and set fast fractions. 
</P>
<P>
	Homespun Fun, who had the No. 6 post, took the 10-horse field  
through the first quarter in 26.4 seconds and then entry mate 
Salinas Hanover took the lead and reached the half mile in 54.1 
seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Salinas Hanover, who was driven by Jack Moiseyev, built a  
two-length lead in the stretch, but Lachance had Ideal Towne 
storming down the middle of the track. The colt had been sixth or 
seventh most of the mile and was fifth entering the stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	``A little before the half I pulled and I was waiting for the  
stretch to pick up the pieces,'' Lachance said. 
</P>
<P>
	John Campbell and Union Guy, who had the No. 8 post, had posted  
the fastest winning time (1:51.4) in winning his elimination on the 
front end last week. This week, they tried to come from behind and 
didn't make it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was following the winner,'' Campbell said. ``He really  
didn't fire as well as I hoped. The last quarter was only 29. There 
was more traffic than you'd like. But the fractions were stiff 
enough that I thought he'd pass more horses than he did.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
