<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baffert Pushes Filly in Derby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Derby or not?  
</P>
<P>
	When the gates opened for today's 125th Kentucky Derby, the  
field of 19 3-year-olds included two fillies -- Excellent Meeting 
and Three Ring. 
</P>
<P>
	Running fillies in the Derby has always been a tough decision  
for owners and trainers, which is why only 36 have competed in the 
first 124 derbies. Just three have won it. 
</P>
<P>
	``No doubt, it's a tough call,'' said trainer D. Wayne Lukas,  
who sent out the last four fillies who ran in the Derby and won it 
with Winning Colors in 1988. ``It's a totally different scenario 
when they run with the colts. It throws them into uncharted 
waters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trainers Bob Baffert and Eddie Plesa decided to take the plunge  
this year, even though their fillies are testing the boys for the 
first time in the 1 1/4-mile race (5:27 p.m. EDT post time) at 
Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert sends out Excellent Meeting, while Plesa saddles Three  
Ring. 
</P>
<P>
	The field was reduced from 20 on Friday when Aljabr, owned by  
Sheikh Mohammed al Maktoum's Godolphin Stable, was scratched, 
leaving Worldly Manner as the Dubai-based stable's only Derby 
entry. 
</P>
<P>
	The reluctance to send fillies against colts is based on several  
factors. Fillies tend to be smaller, lighter and generally more 
fragile. Additionally, some are hesitant to race in close quarters 
because of all the banging that goes on. The races are longer, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Excellent Meeting will be able to take a lot of the  
heat, the dirt, the trip,'' said Baffert, who has three chances to 
win an unprecedented third consecutive Derby. ``She's training 
great over the track, she's peaking, and she can easily win it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Excellent Meeting and General Challenge, both owned by John  
Mabee, will race as an entry and were listed as the third choice in 
early wagering at 6-1; Stephen Got Even, trained by two-time Derby 
winner Nick Zito, was the favorite at 4-1, with Menifee and Vicar 
co-second choices at 5-1. Prime Timber, Baffert's other Derby 
horse, was 12-1 in early wagering. 
</P>
<P>
	Excellent Meeting is unbeaten in three starts this year, while  
Three Ring is coming off a win the Bonnie Miss at Park on March 16. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert waited until Friday before declaring his filly in the  
Derby and out of the Oaks, which was won by Silverbulletday, 
trained by Baffert and owned by Mike Pegram. Plesa never wavered. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you've got an owner and trainer on the same page, it  
makes it easy,'' Plesa said. ``We're in the race to win, not make 
some kind of a statement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Regret was the first filly to win the Derby in 1915; Genuine  
Risk won in 1980 and Winning Colors won in '88. Even the first 
Derby had a filly -- Ascension -- who ran 10th in 1875. 
</P>
<P>
	Two fillies are in a Derby for just the eighth time -- the last  
time it happened was 1984, with Lukas' Life's Magic eighth and 
Althea 19th. 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas, who sends out Cat Thief and Charismatic today in his bid  
for a fourth Derby win, prefers his fillies to go against colts 
before making a Derby decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``Take Winning Colors,'' Lukas said. ``She won by nine at Santa  
Anita, so I knew she could do it. It lets you know they can handle 
the pressure. Fillies are built differently and the filly races are 
considerably easier.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last filly to run in the Derby was Siren's Song, who ran  
16th in Lukas' bid for a third consecutive Derby victory. It's 
Baffert's turn to go for a three-peat, and he's glad to have a 
filly along. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was training her for the Derby all along, and was going to  
leave it up to fate and see how she drew,'' said Baffert, referring 
to Wednesday's draft of post positions. ``And when she drew a 
favorable post, I thought something's telling me she needs to 
run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pegram, who also owns '98 Derby and Preakness winner Real Quiet,  
never considered Silverbulletday for the Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``I learned as a kid that if you're going to pick a fight you  
better have an edge,'' Pegram said. ``There's no edge in a 20-horse 
field.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
