<DOCNO> APW19990501.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 16:31:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lewis' Horse Wins Another Derby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Bob Lewis' epitaph will have to be  
rewritten. 
</P>
<P>
	When he and his wife, Beverly, won the Kentucky Derby in 1997  
with Silver Charm, the beer distributor from Southern California 
said he wanted his tombstone to read: ``Loving husband, adoring 
father and winner of the 123rd Kentucky Derby.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Better make that ``two Kentucky Derbys.''  
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic brought the Lewises back to the winner's circle for  
the second time in three years, winning the 125th Kentucky Derby on 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Lewis held the Derby trophy up with both hands and Beverly  
kept grasping it with her right hand as trainer D. Wayne Lukas and 
jockey Chris Antley joined the celebration. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unbelievable! Unbelievable!'' Lewis said. ``To have this for  
the second time in our lives is just tremendous. You look back, and 
Beverly and I have had such unbelievably good fortune in this 
industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Charismatic wasn't even their best shot for the Derby.  
</P>
<P>
	Seven weeks ago, the Lewis' Exploit was the early favorite.  
Trained by Bob Baffert, Exploit was injured in the San Felipe and 
the Lewis' other hope for the Derby was Charismatic, who was in a 
claiming race on Feb. 11. 
</P>
<P>
	On that day, the son of Summer Squall was up for sale for  
$62,500. There were no takers. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic won the claiming race via disqualification.  
</P>
<P>
	Reminded of that February race, Bob Lewis joked, ``You're  
talking about a long time ago!'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Isn't that incredible?'' he said. ``You can have a claimer  
today and all of a sudden have a champion tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since February, Charismatic could do no better than second in  
his next three races. 
</P>
<P>
	After Charismatic's fourth-place finish in the Santa Anita  
Derby, Lewis was on the fence about whether to send the colt to the 
Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were really on the bubble,'' he said. ``We had about  
80-some-thousand in graded stakes (winnings) in until we got into 
the Lexington.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A win in the April 18 Lexington Stakes at Keeneland earned  
Charismatic his Derby trip, where he wore down the Lukas-trained 
Cat Thief in the stretch and held off fast-closing Menifee as 
Antley stuck his left index finger into the air yards before the 
finish line. 
</P>
<P>
	The former claimer paid $64.60, the third-largest in Derby  
history behind only the $184.90 by Donerail in 1913 and the $72.40 
for Gallahadion in 1940. 
</P>
<P>
	Not a bad day for Lewis, even if it began with a trip to the  
dentist. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he spent the morning in the chair at an emergency dental  
clinic in Lexington, having his bridge repaired after losing a 
tooth at a private party Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had to ride home with a great big hole in the front of my  
mouth,'' Lewis said. ``That tooth is very dear to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas called the Lewises ``the first lady of racing and the  
first gentleman of thoroughbred racing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added Lewis: ``Do you think there's a tombstone large enough to  
say `Winner of the 123rd and 125th Kentucky Derby?''' 
</P>
</TEXT>
