<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-USVI Postmaster Innocent of Rape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- The former postmaster for the U.S. Virgin  
Islands has been cleared of charges that he twice attacked a 
Washington lobbyist while both were in town for a diversity 
seminar. 
</P>
<P>
	Louis Austin Jackson, 48, had been charged with three counts of  
sexual battery and could have faced a maximum 33 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury deliberated less than two hours Friday before acquitting  
him. 
</P>
<P>
	The 41-year-old woman, described as a legislative assistant who  
was working for the postal service, said Jackson fondled her one 
night in his room. She told authorities that he apologized days 
later, saying he was drunk. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Jackson, a married man, went to the woman's  
suite the day the group was checking out of the hotel, overpowered 
her and assaulted her. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson's attorney, Edward Shohat of Miami, said Jackson fell in  
love with the woman over time and she willingly had sex with him. 
Afterward, the woman worried about how the relationship would 
affect her job and feared that her fiance would find out. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson was placed on administrative leave in October after  
seven months as postmaster in Charlotte Amalie. He was fired May 5 
when prosecutors and an independent Postal Service investigation 
found enough evidence to file criminal charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
