<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Galaxy 1, MetroStars 0, SO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Making his MLS debut, Los Angeles  
coach Sigi Schmid beat his former mentor Saturday night when the 
Galaxy overcame a man disadvantage for the final 16 minutes and 
outlasted the New York-New Jersey MetroStars in a shootout after a 
0-0 draw. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmid, an assistant to MetroStars coach Bora Miluntinovic when  
the latter led the United States in the 1994 World Cup, was at the 
helm of the Galaxy for his first game since being named to his post 
with Los Angeles on April 22. 
</P>
<P>
	He was at the Galaxy's game against San Jose two days later, a  
1-0 victory, but was not behind the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Caligiuri, Mauricio Cienfuegos and Greg Vanney scored to  
give Los Angeles the 3-2 margin of victory in the shootout. 
</P>
<P>
	The MetroStars failed to take advantage of the man advantage  
after Galaxy forward Clint Mathis was red-carded for a tackle on 
New York-New Jersey defender Mark Semioli in the 74th minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Semioli was shielding ball to let it roll over the touchline  
when Mathis attempted a slide tackle that got nowhere near the ball 
but brought Semioli down hard. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss was the second straight for the MetroStars, whose  
scoreless streak was extended to 242 minutes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
